Nic},"Gpt-5.2-medium":{model:UcBd.cwa,Nl:UcQsb.M1b},"Gpt-5.2-high":{model:UcBd.cwa,Nl:UcQsb.MAb},"Gpt-5.4-mini-medium":{model:UcBd.Gjn,Nl:UcQsb.M1b}},
UcJMk={model:UcBd.cwa,Nl:void 0};var UcKMk=` ### CloudVizGenerator / "Cloud Frame" special considerations
#### Definition of a CloudVizGenerator / "Cloud Frame"
A *CloudVizGenerator*, or its user-facing name *"Cloud Frame"*, is a special canvas entity that automatically generates
diagrams of users' cloud data based on user-set layout settings. This document may contain one.

#### Warning

 Lucid AI *does not yet have the tools* to edit the layout of the cloud frame nor edit in any way the blocks inside of it.
 Users may not be aware of this limitation, so you must be *very careful* about accidentally attempting to edit them.
 IMPORTANT: A caveat to previous instructions about the ${UcAd.J2c} agent: ALWAYS, BEFORE handing over control to the agent,
 MAKE SURE the user's request does not pertain to any generated blocks belonging to a Cloud Frame.
 IMPORTANT: NEVER switch the ${UcAd.J2c} agent to edit these shapes in any way! The agent WILL fail -- and failing is really really bad.

#### Identification of generated/cloud frame items

 Shapes, containers, and lines returned by *Canvas Query* carry a \`belongsToCloudFrame\` field that is set to \`true\` when the item was generated by a Cloud Frame. Shapes and containers returned by *GetDataBackedShapes* may also carry that field. The field is omitted otherwise.
 If the user's request appears to relate to any item marked \`belongsToCloudFrame: true\`, **do not attempt to edit it**.

#### Other Cloud Frame features
    Here are some features of Cloud Frames that users might ask for. Again, lucid Ai does not have the tools to perform any of these:
- changing the *layout settings*, hierarchy or structure
- creating, deleting, duplicating, exporting or swapping *"views"*
- adding, removing, hiding or filtering blocks
- *collapse*/*summarize* or *expand*/*unsummarize* shapes or resource types. Summarization here refers to combining multiple shapes into a single shape, not a text-based summary of data.

#### Recovery behavior

 Instead:
   - politely inform the user that the Cloud Agent Beta does not yet have the ability to edit content within Cloud Frames.
   - Be clear that this is a limitation of Lucid AI
   - Instruct the user they'll have to make any desired edits manually.`;var UcLMk={Fe:UcDd.a2f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-documents-activity"),description:['## Role\nFind documents by recent **activity** — viewed, edited, commented on, or created — for the current user, optionally narrowed to a time window, specific activity types, or documents worked on with specific collaborators.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Return the user\'s most recently active documents, ranked by activity recency.\n- Filter by activity type (viewed / edited / commented / created), a time window (since / until), and/or collaborator user IDs.\n- Each result includes the document\'s id and activity signals — edit / comment / view counts, last-activity timestamps, and whether the current user created it.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use this tool for recency / activity questions: "what was I working on", "docs I edited last week", "what did John and I collaborate on recently".\n- Populate only the filters the user actually implied; leave the rest unset. With no filters, the tool returns the user\'s recently active documents from roughly the last 30 days.\n\n## Limitations\n- Results are scoped to documents the current user already has access to.\n- It returns document IDs and activity statistics — not full document contents.\n- It cannot create, edit, share, rename, or delete documents.\n- This is recency / activity-based, not keyword or topic search.']};var UcMMk={Fe:UcDd.E_e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!1,description:"## Role\n\nPackages user-provided text content into a .txt file and adds it to the process context frame. The file contents are automatically extracted from the most recent message the user proactively sent — you only need to provide a file name.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The **most recent user message** contains structured or substantial text content that will be used for diagram generation — this includes process specs, flow definitions, SOPs, procedures, workflows, step lists, or any structured data describing a process\n- The content is **proactively shared** by the user as reference material, not a reply to a question you asked\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- Content is a **short reply or answer** to a question you asked\n- Content is clearly **unrelated to the process**\n- User **explicitly states** the content is not for process documentation\n\n## Key Behaviors\n\n- **Always call this tool before any content generation tools** (e.g., GenerateDiagram, CreateDiagramOutline) to persist context first\n- When uncertain, **err on the side of adding** — missing context is worse than adding extra, since users can always delete unwanted context\n- Can be called **alongside other tools** (not a terminator)\n"};var UcNMk={Fe:UcDd.G_e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!1,description:"**Add Chat Notes to Process Context Frame Tool**\n\nRecords clarifications and chat notes about the process to the process context frame on the document.\n\n**When to Use:**\n- ALWAYS call this tool after the user responds to AskClarifyingQuestions tool. Only include questions the user explicitly answered — skip vague or ambiguous responses.\n- When the user provides important context or clarifications about the process.\n\n**When NOT to Use:**\n- For general conversational responses that do not resolve a specific ambiguity about the process.\n- When the user is asking a question rather than providing an answer.\n- When the chat note (or a semantically equivalent one) already exists in the context frame.\n\n**Key Behaviors:**\n- Rephrase chat notes to third-person — the Q&A is visible to all document collaborators.\n- Be concise. 1 question and 1 answer per chat note. Split up complex chat notes into multiple simpler ones if needed.\n- Check existing chat notes in the context frame (### Context Frame Content -> #### Chat Notes section in the system prompt) to avoid duplicate chat notes.\n- Can be called alongside other tools (not a terminator).\n- Multiple chat notes can be added in a single call.\n"};var UcOMk={Fe:UcDd.H_e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to insert additional rows or columns into an existing dynamic table on the canvas. Use this when the user asks to "add a row", "add another sprint", "add columns for Q3 and Q4", etc., on a table that already exists.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The dynamic table must already exist — pass the generatorId from the result of CreateDynamicTable or CanvasQuery.\n- The table must already be pivoted on the field whose values you want to add. This tool does NOT change the pivot. If the current pivot doesn\'t match, call EditDynamicTableMetadata first.\n\n## Behavior\n- Labels are added as values for the table\'s CURRENT row/column pivot.\n- On a card-backed Lucid field pivot (Status, Assignee, Sprint, etc.) labels become the row/column\'s actual values.\n- On the default custom-field pivot, labels are dropped and blank headers are inserted (pass empty strings if you simply want N more blank rows/columns).\n- For enum pivots other than Assignee/User (Status, Sprint, Priority, Issue Type, etc.), labels that don\'t match an existing collection entry are rejected. Use EditDynamicTableMetadata to switch pivots if the label would match a different pivot.\n- On a block-visual pivot (Fill Color, Line Color, Emojis, Tags) or an auto-derived pivot, the call fails — switch the pivot first via EditDynamicTableMetadata.\n- New rows/columns are always appended at the end. Insertion at an index is not supported.\n- All inserted entries are committed in a single undo batch.\n\n## Assignee/User pivot — special handling\n\nThe Assignee (User) pivot is the only enum pivot that accepts arbitrary new labels, so it needs extra care:\n\n- **"Unassigned" is inherent to the pivot. Never pass it as a label.** On the User pivot, "Unassigned" is the display name for the *no-value state of the assignee field itself* — any card whose assignee is empty is rendered in the "Unassigned" group automatically, as a property of the User enum. It is not a separate user, not a separate row, and not something you add. If the user asks to "add an Unassigned row/column" or "make a column for unassigned items", do **not** call this tool with that label — passing `"Unassigned"` (or variants like `"No assignee"`, `"None"`, `"N/A"`, `"TBD"`) creates a bogus custom user with that literal name, which is exactly the failure mode we want to avoid. Instead, explain that the Unassigned group already exists as part of how the pivot works, and ensure any cards that should fall into it simply have no assignee set.\n- **Labels that resolve to a real Lucid user** (matched by display name or email) bind to that user. Prefer this whenever the user gives a real name or email — the tool will find and use the Lucid account automatically.\n- **Labels that don\'t resolve to any Lucid user** are added as a **custom assignee** — a free-text, non-Lucid-user entry that still renders and groups like a real assignee. This is the right behavior for any named person the user supplies who doesn\'t have a Lucid account, including: external collaborators ("Marketing lead", an outside vendor), TBD owners, and plain placeholder people ("Jane Doe", "John Smith") that the user is using to sketch out a plan. Custom assignees are a feature, not a fallback — use them freely when the user has named someone, real or placeholder. The only thing you should not do is silently invent assignees the user never mentioned (when no one has been named, leave the pivot empty and ask for assignees in a post-creation refinement).\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot change the pivot — use EditDynamicTableMetadata for that.\n- Cannot insert at a specific index (always appended).\n- Cannot remove or rename existing rows/columns.\n- Cannot create the table — use CreateDynamicTable for that.']};var UcPMk={Fe:UcDd.I_e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!1,description:"## Role\n\nAdds uploaded files to the persistent process context frame on the document, making them part of the permanent process documentation.\n\nWhen to Use:\n- When user uploads files clearly containing **process-related content** (SOPs, procedures, templates, workflows, documentation, guidelines, steps) meant for process documentation\n- When user uploads images that are **clearly process-related** (photos of whiteboards, diagrams, flowcharts, screenshots of tools or processes) meant for process documentation\n- When user **states clearly** to add uploaded files as part of the process documentation\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- Files uploaded only for **one-off questions** (no intent to document)\n- Files clearly **unrelated to the process** (personal files, photos, test data)\n- User **explicitly states** file is NOT part of process documentation\n- **No files** have been uploaded yet\n\n## File Reference Format\n\n- Files in conversation history have references in the format `{uuid}_{index}` (e.g. `cdf46ea1-3bda-4df7-a244-36222ebf9aef_0`)\n- All files have their respective reference as a header in the message content (e.g. `[File Reference: cdf46ea1-3bda-4df7-a244-36222ebf9aef_0]`)\n- File references are **unique** across the whole conversation\n\n## Key Behaviors\n\n- **Always call this tool proactively** if the above criteria is met — call before AskClarifyingQuestionTool or any other tool to ensure files are added to context before any other operations\n- When uncertain, **err on the side of adding** — duplicates are auto-skipped and users can remove them if irrelevant\n- Added files **persist across sessions** and become permanent blocks on the context frame\n- **Audio/video files** are stored as transcript text files (e.g. `recording.mp3` becomes `recording_transcript.txt`) — the original binary is not stored\n- **Automatic duplicate detection** based on file content — duplicates are skipped\n- Can be called **alongside other tools** (not a terminator)\n- The tool outputs which files were **added** and which were **skipped** (duplicates or invalid references)\n- Only available **after switching to the process agent** — consider adding files before the process agent was active if they meet criteria\n- **Evaluate each file reference separately** — do not batch-assume all should be added/skipped\n- Users can **remove files** from the context frame, so re-add if a deleted file is re-uploaded or specifically referenced — but be cautious about re-adding to avoid frustrating the user\n"};var UcQMk={Fe:UcDd.J_e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:["## Role\nUse this tool to add existing canvas blocks onto an existing dynamic table.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The blocks must already exist on the canvas (e.g., created via ImportJiraToBoard or AddBlock).\n- A dynamic table must already exist — Use the CanvasQuery tool to discover this dynamic table, and if there are none, use the CreateDynamicTable tool.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Places existing blocks onto a specific dynamic table\n- Blocks are added to the table according to its current pivot configuration\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId returned by the CreateDynamicTable tool\n- Use block IDs returned by other tools such as ImportJiraToBoard or AddBlock\n- Call this AFTER both the blocks and the dynamic table have been created\n\n## Limitations\n- Does not create blocks or dynamic tables — use other tools for that\n- Only works with dynamic table generators, not other generator types\n- Only adds blocks that support being contained by a dynamic table (e.g., cards); other blocks are silently skipped"]};var UcRMk={Fe:UcDd.K_e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:["## Role\nUse this tool to add existing canvas Lucid cards onto an existing Lucid timeline.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The Lucid card blocks must already exist on the canvas (e.g., created via ImportJiraToBoard, CreateBlock with class `LucidCardBlock`, or already imported from another integration).\n- A timeline must already exist — Use the CanvasQuery tool to discover this timeline, and if there are none, use the CreateLucidTimeline tool.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Places existing Lucid cards onto a specific timeline as tasks\n- Handles date processing automatically for cards with or without date fields\n\n## What can be added\n**ONLY Lucid card blocks (`LucidCardBlock`) can be added to a timeline.** Every other block type is rejected — The tool will report any rejected IDs.\n\nIf the user wants to put non-card content on the timeline, notify the user that:\n- Only Lucid card blocks can be put onto timelines.\n- offer to convert the none card blocks into cards (either via conversion, or by creating cards and copying the data over).\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId returned by the CreateLucidTimeline tool\n- Call this AFTER both the cards and the timeline are on the canvas\n\n## Limitations\n- Does not create blocks or timelines — use other tools for that\n- Only works with timeline generators, not other generator types\n- Only Lucid cards are accepted; all other block types are rejected"]};var UcSMk={Fe:UcDd.d2f,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to add one of the prebuilt **shape banks** to the canvas. A shape bank is a floating panel of pre-styled, draggable shapes (e.g. story-point circles, t-shirt-size circles, profile/people shapes). Users drag individual shapes out of the bank to place them; the bank itself sits alongside the workspace.\n\n## Supported shape banks\n- **ProfileShapeBank** — a panel of person/profile shapes prepopulated with the document\'s current online collaborators and the active user. Use when the user wants people, faces, or team members on the canvas (e.g. "add a profile bank", "add the team", "show who\'s on the project", "add people shapes").\n- **StoryPointEstimation** — Fibonacci story-point circles (1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21) for sprint estimation. Use when the user mentions story points, sprint estimation, or agile pointing.\n- **TshirtSizeEstimation** — t-shirt size circles (XS, S, M, L, XL, XXL) for rough sizing. Use when the user mentions t-shirt sizing.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Inserts one shape bank at a sensible auto-position, or at an explicit X/Y if provided.\n- Loads the bank\'s underlying library on demand if it isn\'t already loaded.\n- Profile bank: the document\'s online collaborators and the active user are filled in automatically. The LLM does NOT need to specify users.\n- Estimation banks: the circle values, colors, and title are preset by Lucid; the LLM does NOT pass any contents.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Pick the right `shapeBank` enum value based on the user\'s intent.\n- Leave `x` and `y` unset unless the user specifies a location or you need to place the bank near another item.\n- Each call inserts ONE bank. To add multiple banks (e.g. story-point and t-shirt together for an estimation session), call the tool multiple times.\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot create custom shape banks — only the three kinds above.\n- Cannot add or remove individual shapes from a bank — banks come with their fixed contents.\n- The Profile bank pulls from the document\'s *current* online collaborators; users not connected at the moment of insertion are not added.']};var UcTMk={Fe:UcDd.z7a,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nThis is your primary tool for *reading* and *querying* the canvas or document. It retrieves items from the canvas based on your query criteria and returns their JSON representation with the properties you request.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThis tool uses a **two-stage filtering pipeline**:\n\n1. **Deterministic Filters** (*TextPattern*, *ColorSearch*, *ShapeTypes*, *Regions*, *User Viewport) — rule-based filters that narrow results precisely; all active filters are combined with **AND logic** (items must satisfy *every* specified filter)\n2. **AI Semantic Search** (via *SelectionCriteria*) — an AI subagent interprets your natural language description and further refines results; use this when the query involves open-ended categories or concepts that deterministic filters cannot express. Leave SelectionCriteria empty when deterministic filters are sufficient — deterministic filters are faster and more precise\n\nAfter both stages, an optional **Proximity Expansion** (*ItemsInProximity*) can include nearby items for additional context.\n\nYou also control **which properties** appear in the output via *BlockProperties*, *LucidCardBlockProperties*, and *LineProperties*. Only request the properties you need to keep the response focused.\n\n## General Usage Guidelines\n\n- These are general guidelines; follow any system prompt instructions you have as to how to use this tool first.\n- Only use this tool when the existing context, conversation history, and previous tools\' outputs are NOT sufficient.  Many times they will be, including IDs of new blocks, and status updates.\n- For selection-scoped edits, existing context is not sufficient if the target ID came from an older selection. Use *ParseSelectionOnly* when the latest selection context is missing, ambiguous, or lacks needed fields.\n- This tool returns raw JSON data; not summaries, takeaways, or generalizations.\n- Do **NOT** use this tool to discover the exact result of a delete command that utilized \'healConnections\' unless it is ABSOLUTELY VITAL to your immediate task.\n- Default to using only the Deterministic filters whenever possible - they are much faster than selection criteria.\n- Use no deterministic filters or selection criteria to read everything about the document.  Again, this should be rare.\n\n## Examples\n\n### Basic: Find items by text\n> User says "I need to finish up the items marked TODO before our sprint review"\n- **TextPattern**: "TODO"\n- **SelectionCriteria**: "" (deterministic filter is sufficient)\n\n### Semantic: Meaning-based query\n> User says "Help me prepare for our architecture review — what are the key decision points in this workflow?"\n- **SelectionCriteria**: "main decision points in the workflow"\n- **Why**: "Decision point" is a semantic concept — a shape might be labeled "Approve?" or "Route A vs B" without literally containing the word "decision". No regex alternation pattern can reliably capture this because it requires understanding the shape\'s *role* in the workflow, not just its text.\n\n### Filter by user viewport\n> User says "Can you walk me through this diagram?", while they have nothing selected on the canvas.\n- **FilterToUserViewport**: true\n- **Why**: The user asked for a walkthrough of a specific diagram, but provided no additional context to narrow down which diagram they are talking about.  It is likely that they are looking at a specific portion of the canvas and want to understand what it is they are looking at.\n\n### Multiple filters: text + proximity\n> User says "I\'m checking what might be blocked — show me what\'s near the shapes that mention deadlines or due dates"\n- **TextPattern**: "deadline|due date|due by|overdue|timeline"\n- **ItemsInProximity**: 15\n- **SelectionCriteria**: ""\n- **Why**: Regex finds deadline-related shapes, then proximity expansion pulls in their neighbors for context.',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-reading-canvas")};var UcUMk={Fe:UcDd.O1,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'This tool converts existing shapes on the canvas from one type to another. Use this tool when the user wants to transform, convert, or change the type of shapes.\n\n## IMPORTANT: Check canBeChangedTo First\nBefore using this tool, query the target blocks with CanvasQuery and request the "CanBeChangedTo" block property. This property lists valid target shape types for each block. Shape changes ONLY work within exchange groups - you cannot convert a shape to an arbitrary type.\n\nIf the user\'s requested target shape is NOT in the block\'s canBeChangedTo list, DO NOT use this tool.\n\n## When to Use\n- User asks to convert shapes to a different type AND the target is in canBeChangedTo\n- User wants to transform shapes while preserving content and position\n- The target shape type is a valid exchange within the same group\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Target shape type is NOT in the block\'s canBeChangedTo list (use delete + create instead)\n- User wants to create new shapes (use *CreateBlock* instead)\n- User wants to change visual properties (use *EditBlockStyle* for color, *ResizeBlock* for size instead)\n\n## Examples\n- "Turn these flowchart shapes into different flowchart shapes" -> Check canBeChangedTo, use this tool if valid\n- "Convert sticky notes to process blocks" -> Likely NOT in canBeChangedTo, use delete + create approach\n- "Change these rectangles to circles" -> Check canBeChangedTo first'};var UcVMk={Fe:UcDd.Z3,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nProduces highly targeted, specification-driven summaries of a large canvas/document by operating on spatial chunks.\n\n## Critical Requirement — additionalPrompt Usage\n\n- **General summarization:** Leave additionalPrompt *empty* — the tool will use appropriate defaults based on selection\n- **Filtered summarization:** Provide specific filtering instructions in additionalPrompt, e.g., "Locate and summarize all error-related content"\n\n## How It Works\n\n- The overall document is split into **spatially/semantically coherent chunks**\n- This tool is called **once per chunk** with your summary instructions\n- For each chunk, it extracts only information that **matches your request** and returns a dense, factual summary\n- Chunks with **no relevant information** are effectively ignored, so unrelated content does not pollute the final result\n- Outputs are optimized for **tool-to-tool communication** — compact, information-dense, and free of visual/styling noise\n\n## Selection Handling\n\nThe tool automatically detects what to summarize:\n- **Shapes selected** → summarizes only those selected shapes\n- **No shapes selected** → summarizes the entire document\n\n## Behavior Guarantees\n\n- Focuses on **content, not presentation** — ignores styling, coordinates, fonts, and colors unless they carry explicit semantic meaning (e.g., colors encode status or type)\n- **Strict about relevance** — if a chunk does not clearly match your requested topics and include criteria, it returns no effective summary for that chunk\n- Resulting chunk summaries are:\n  - **Dense, factual, and faithful** to the underlying diagrams and notes\n  - **Easy to merge** into a final, document-level summary by a coordinating tool\n\n## When to Use\n\n- When the user specifically asks for a **summary of the document** or a piece of it — *the user must be referring to document contents, as this tool only works on the current document*\n- When the user asks something that implies wanting a summary, like:\n  - "Tell me about this diagram"\n  - "What is this mindmap about?"\n- When the user asks for tasks, action items, to-dos, assignments, next steps, or a checklist based on the document content\n  - "Give me some tasks based on this board"\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- When the user asks for a summary of **anything other than document contents**\n  - If the user wants to summarize a file they uploaded, text they pasted, or anything else not on the document — message the user a summary manually instead\n',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-summarizing")};var UcWMk={Fe:UcDd.e6f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'**Conventional Board Review Tool**: Loads the canonical checklist of conventional rules for a single diagram type (UML, BPMN, Flowchart, ERD) and **kicks off an active review of the user\'s board** against those rules.\n\n## When to Use\n- User asks for a "conventional review", "diagram review", "convention check", "best-practice review", or "what should I improve" on their diagram.\n- User explicitly references one of the supported diagram types and asks for feedback on it.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- User asks to change content, styling, or layout — use Rewrite / EditBlockStyle / Recommend*Layout tools instead.\n- User asks about a diagram type that is not one of UML, BPMN, Flowchart, ERD.\n\n## Required Parameter Discipline\n- This tool requires a `diagramType` of `UML`, `BPMN`, `Flowchart`, or `ERD`.\n- You may ONLY supply `diagramType` directly when the user **explicitly named** one of those four types (or a close synonym — e.g. "class diagram" → UML, "process diagram" → BPMN, "flow chart" → Flowchart, "entity relationship" / "database schema" / "data model" → ERD) **in their most recent message**.\n- **Canvas content alone is NOT enough.** Even if the board obviously contains an ERD or flowchart, you MUST call `AskClarifyingQuestions` first unless the user typed the type name. The user may legitimately want to review the board as a different lens than what\'s drawn.\n- If the user did not explicitly name the type, call `AskClarifyingQuestions` first with the four options, then call this tool with their answer.\n\n## Clarifying Question Discipline\nWhen you call `AskClarifyingQuestions` before this tool, ask **EXACTLY ONE question** — the diagram type — with options `UML`, `BPMN`, `Flowchart`, `ERD` (single-select). Do NOT add any additional questions about:\n- Review depth / thoroughness / scope (this tool always evaluates every rule in its checklist — depth is not configurable).\n- Which areas of the board to focus on (the rule set is fixed per diagram type).\n- Output format, length, or style.\n- Anything else.\nAdding a second question wastes a user turn on a parameter this tool does not accept.\n\n## After Calling This Tool — Critical Behavior\nThe tool\'s result is a **review prompt**, not a final answer. It contains the rule list AND instructions to evaluate each rule against the actual board and output the findings in a fixed format. You MUST:\n1. Give a verdict for **every** rule in the list. Do not skip any. The four verdicts (used verbatim in the user-facing output) are:\n   - **Recommended changes** — rule applies and the board clearly deviates from it. Concrete change the user should make; cite evidence.\n   - **Recommended checks** — rule applies and the board appears to deviate, but the deviation may be intentional. Explain both the observation and the possible justification so the user can decide.\n   - **Strengths** — rule applies and the board follows it. Briefly note what the board does well.\n   - **N/A** — the rule does not apply because the construct it checks is absent from this board.\n2. Use `FilterCanvas` or `CanvasQuery` as needed to inspect the diagram before deciding.\n3. Call `MessageUser` using the exact bullet-list output format specified in the tool result. The output is a single flat bullet list — one bullet per finding, shape `- **<Verdict>** **<Rule title>**: <evidence>` — ordered by verdict priority. Show at most 2 Strengths bullets. Follow the format verbatim.\n\n**Do NOT simply echo the rule list back to the user.** The user wants per-rule verdicts grounded in the board, not the raw checklist. **Do NOT rename the verdict labels** ("Issues", "Problems", "Suggestions", "Warnings", "Pass", "Compliant", etc. are all wrong — use Recommended changes / Recommended checks / Strengths / N/A only).\n\nDo not call this tool more than once per turn; do not call it for multiple diagram types in the same turn.\n'};var UcXMk={Fe:UcDd.S$d,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\nCopies or duplicates **existing** items that are already on the canvas.\nThis tool requires item IDs and preserves all intrinsic properties such as text, color, or size from the originals (does not preserve emoji reactions or comments).\n\n## When to Use This Tool\n- To duplicate existing items while preserving their properties\n- To copy items into a different container or location\n- To move items by copying then deleting the originals\n\n## When NOT to Use This Tool\n- To create *new* items — use *CreateBlock* (or *CreateLine*) instead\n- When you don't have valid item IDs to copy\n\n## Placement Guidelines\n- **Pasting into a diagram/container**: Use `assistedLayoutPlacement` with the container's ID and optionally `row`/`column`. Using X/Y coordinates will place items *outside* the container.\n- **Pasting on empty canvas**: Use X/Y coordinates or omit placement for default offset behavior."};var UcYMk={Fe:UcDd.p1e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nAttach AI suggestion callouts to existing canvas blocks. Each suggestion is anchored to a single block\nand shown to the user as a card the user can act on, dismiss, or ignore. There can only be at most one\nactive suggestion per block.\n\n## When to Use\n- After analyzing the canvas and identifying concrete, block-specific issues or improvements that\n  the user should review before any change is applied.\n- When clarification is needed about a specific block before you can proceed (use **contextNeeded**).\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- For general advice or status that isn't tied to a specific canvas block — use **MessageUser** instead.\n- To apply edits directly. This tool only surfaces a suggestion; it does not modify the document.\n- For blocks you have not yet observed on the canvas. The **itemId** must reference a real block.\n\n## How Many\n- Surface only the **most impactful** issues — aim for **3-4 suggestions per review**, not one for every item.\n- A focused handful the user can act on beats an exhaustive list. When reviewing a frame or the whole board, pick the highest-value observations rather than commenting on everything.\n- Include **at least one of each suggestion type** in a multi-suggestion review rather than defaulting to all of one — see the **SuggestionType** parameter for when each applies.\n\n## After Creating\n- The suggestions render as cards on the canvas, so **do not restate or summarize them in chat**. A short pointer (e.g. \"I've added a few suggestions to the canvas — click any to see the details.\") is all that's needed; don't repeat each suggestion's content in your message.\n\n## How It Works\n- You provide a list of suggestions, each with an **itemId**, **suggestionType**, **title**, and **description**.\n- For each suggestion, a callout appears next to the referenced block.\n- Suggestions whose **itemId** does not exist on the canvas are skipped. Do not invent IDs.\n\n## Avoiding Duplicates\n- **Always call *ReadAiSuggestions* first** to see what is already on the canvas before creating any.\n- **NEVER** create a suggestion for an **itemId** that already appears there. Suggestions for blocks\n  that already have an active suggestion are skipped."};var UcZMk={Fe:UcDd.Lk,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nCreate a single new block on the canvas with only class, variant, position, and size. Does NOT set colors, text, card data, or other properties — use the dedicated EditBlock* sub-tools for those after creation.\n\n## When to Use\n- Adding a new block, shape, or frame to the canvas.\n- If you don't already know the className, use ShapeLibraryTool to search, then ShapeDetailsTool for variants and advanced properties.\n\n## Custom Shape Libraries\n- ShapeLibraryTool may return shapes from user-created custom libraries (libraryId starting with `custom:`). For those, pass the shape's URI (the `ToolboxId` field from ShapeLibraryTool, which is a full URL) as `blockClass` and the `custom:`-prefixed library id as `library`. Do NOT pass `variant` — custom-library shapes don't use variants. The tool resolves the underlying class (including FreehandBlock for hand-drawn custom shapes and grouped placement for custom shapes that contain multiple constituent blocks) and applies the library's stored geometry/stencil automatically.\n\n## Rules\n- Emit one call per block. To create multiple blocks, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- The tool returns the newly-created blockId in its result; reuse that ID in any follow-up EditBlock* calls."};var Uc_Mk={Fe:UcDd.hRh,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'This tool creates a diagram key (legend block) that shows the unique shape types used in a specified diagram container.\n\n## When to Use\n- The user asks for a diagram key, legend, or shape key for an existing diagram\n- The user wants a visual summary of the shapes used in their diagram\n- Examples: "Create a key for this diagram", "Add a legend showing what each shape means"\n\n## Input\n- diagramId: The container block ID of the diagram to create a key for'};var Uc0Mk={Fe:UcDd.q1e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!1,description:"**Create Diagram Outline Tool**\n\nConverts an existing diagram into a structured SOP (Standard Operating Procedure) outline and places it as a block on the canvas.\n\n**When to Use:**\n- When the user wants a text-based procedure document on the canvas (often called an SOP or Diagram Outline).\n\n**Requirements:**\n- A diagram must be present on the canvas.\n- The diagramId parameter must be the ID of a container surrounding the diagram. The container ID returned by the GenerateDiagram tool can be used for this purpose.\n"};var Uc1Mk={Fe:UcDd.r1e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to create a new dynamic table on the canvas. A dynamic table is a grid-based visualization with customizable row and column headers that can hold cards and data-backed items. It is different from a static table — dynamic tables support grouping, filtering, and syncing with external data sources like Jira.\n\nIf the user asks for "a table" without specifying "dynamic table", you should still use this tool — dynamic tables are the standard table type in Lucid.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Create a new empty dynamic table on the current page\n- By default, creates a blank 2x2 table with empty headers\n- Optionally specify custom row and/or column labels when the user explicitly requests them\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- If the user just asks for a table without specifying rows/columns, omit both parameters to create a blank 2x2 table\n- Only provide row/column labels when the user explicitly names them (e.g. "rows should be Sprint 1, Sprint 2")\n- After creating it, ask the user "Do you want me to import cards from an integration like Jira" but do not ask for any jira details until they confirm.\n## Response Guidelines\n- The Generator ID returned by this tool is for internal use only — do not mention it to the user\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot modify existing tables — this tool only creates new ones\n- Creates an empty table — cards or items must be added separately by the user']};var Uc2Mk={Fe:UcDd.HS,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nCreate a single connector (line/arrow) between two endpoints. Each endpoint may be pinned to a block or to an absolute (x, y) canvas position, with optional endpoint style (e.g. arrow shape).\n\n## When to Use\n- Connecting two blocks with a line or arrow.\n- Drawing a free-floating connector between two canvas coordinates.\n\n## Rules\n- Emit one call per connector. To create multiple connectors, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- Either (BlockId) or both (X, Y) must be provided on each endpoint."};var Uc3Mk={Fe:UcDd.u1e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:["## Role\nUse this tool to create a new Lucid timeline visualization on the canvas.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Create a new timeline visualization on the Lucid canvas with a specified date range\n- Uses the specified time unit (days, weeks, sprints, months, or quarter) regardless of the date range\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Provide start and end dates in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD)\n- The end date must be after the start date\n- Provide a time unit (days, weeks, sprints, months, or quarter). Pick it from the user's framing, not the raw span:\n    - **Sprints** when the user mentions sprints, Scrum, or agile cadences.\n    - **Weeks** for short projects (≤ ~2 months) or anything described week-by-week.\n    - **Months** for medium-range plans (~2–9 months) — the most common default.\n    - **Quarter** for roadmaps, annual plans, or anything described in Q1/Q2/H1/H2 terms.\n    - **Days** only when the user is planning day-level work (a launch week, a hackathon, etc.) — rarely the right default.\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot modify existing timelines — this tool only creates new ones\n- Creates an empty timeline — items must be added separately"]};var Uc4Mk={Fe:UcDd.tRh,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"**Create Process Header Tool**\n\nCreates a formatted header block for a process diagram containing the process title, owner, last updated date, and scope description.\n"};var Uc5Mk={Fe:UcDd.v1e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"## Role\n\nDelegate a focused side-task to a generic subagent that runs in isolation and reports its result back. The subagent has broad tool and skill access.\n\n## When to use this vs. switch_agent\n\n- Use **create_subagent** when you need a *focused result* and want to continue your own conversation afterward.\n- Use **switch_agent** when the user's *whole next-turn request* is better handled by another agent entirely.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- The subagent does NOT see this conversation's history. The `prompt` must be self-contained.\n- The subagent cannot itself call create_subagent.\n- Use `name` to give the task a short display label shown to the user.\n- Use `model` and `reasoning` to dial compute: pick a smaller model for straightforward tasks, a more capable one for tasks requiring judgment.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-subagent-created")};var Uc6Mk={Fe:UcDd.zAb,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nDeletes items (shapes, sticky notes, lines, visual activities, etc.) from the canvas.\n\nNo lines or other shapes are affected by these deletions unless the healConnections flag is on, in which case the system attempts to bridge the gaps left by deleted blocks automatically. Visual activity deletion does not use connection healing.\n\n## Examples of user requests that indicate this tool should be used\n- "Delete the sticky note"\n- "Clear the items"\n\n## Heal Connections Behavior\n\nWhen `healConnections` is enabled, the system automatically bridges gaps by connecting each predecessor of the deleted block to each successor. This works transitively — if you delete a consecutive chain of nodes, predecessors are connected all the way through to the first surviving successor. You can **predict the resulting connections** from the current Lymtex without needing to re-query the canvas:\n- If A→B→C, deleting B with heal creates A→C\n- If A→B→C→D, deleting B and C with heal creates A→D\n- If A→B and C→B and B→D, deleting B with heal creates A→D and C→D'};var Uc7Mk={Fe:UcDd.vNb,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:['## Role\n\nGenerates an AI summary of changes made to the current document since a given point in time.\n\n## What This Tool Does\n\n- Compares the document\'s current state against its state at a given anchor timestamp\n- Produces a short title and summary of what changed (shapes added, edits made, etc.)\n- Focus on high-level changes that would convey meaningful updates to a user who hasn\'t viewed the document in a while, rather than an exhaustive change log\n\n## When to Use\n\n- User asks what changed on a document since they last visited\n- User wants to catch up on changes made by collaborators since a specific date\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- Do not use for general document summarization (use *Summarize* instead)\n- Do not use if the user wants to summarize selected shapes or a specific area\n\n## Resolving the SinceTimestamp\n\nThe **SinceTimestamp** param must be an ISO 8601 timestamp. Use the current date/time and timezone below to resolve relative expressions like "last week" or "3 days ago", and to format timestamps for the user.\nCurrent date/time in ISO 8601: ',
()=>(new Date).toISOString(),"\nUser's local time: ",()=>(new Date).toLocaleTimeString(),"\n"]};var Uc8Mk={Fe:UcDd.Byd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nUpdate LucidCard-specific data fields on a single card block: Title, Description, Status, Owner, Estimate, TshirtSize, StartTime, EndTime.\n\n## When to Use\n- Changing a card's title, description, or any of its structured fields.\n- Setting or changing a card's status, owner, estimate, t-shirt size, or date range.\n\n## Rules\n- Dates must be ISO 8601 (e.g. \"2024-01-15\").\n- Emit one call per card. To edit multiple cards, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- Only fields you want to change need to be set; omit the rest."};var Uc9Mk={Fe:UcDd.I2c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nUpdate the visual style of a single existing block: FillColor, LineColor, LineWidth, and StrokeStyle.\n\n## When to Use\n- Changing fill or border color of a block.\n- Changing border width or stroke style (solid, dashed, dotted) of a block.\n\n## Rules\n- Emit one call per block. To restyle multiple blocks, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- Only fields you want to change need to be set; omit the rest."};var Uc$Mk={Fe:UcDd.z2e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"This tool edits the most recently generated board layout.\n\n## Requirements\n- A board MUST have been previously generated with the TextToBoard tool in this session.\n- If no prior board exists, this tool will return an error.\n\n## When to use this tool\nUse this tool when the user wants to make changes to a board that was just generated with TextToBoard.\n\n## When NOT to use this tool\n- Do NOT use this tool if no board has been generated yet — call TextToBoard first.\n- Do NOT use this tool to create a completely new board — use TextToBoard instead.\n\n## After using this tool\n- State what was changed in a single sentence.\n- Do NOT ask follow-up questions or suggest next steps unprompted.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-board")};var UcaNk={Fe:UcDd.A2e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to modify the settings of an existing dynamic table after it has been created.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The dynamic table must already exist — use the generatorId of the dynamic table on the canvas.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Enable or disable agile capacity planning\n- Toggle load tracking graphic visibility\n- Set row and column pivots (grouping fields) to organize data by assignee, status, priority, or custom fields\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId from an existing dynamic table on the canvas\n- Only provide the fields you want to change — omit other fields to keep them unchanged\n- For pivots, use semantic field names for standard fields: "assignee", "status", "priority", "parent", "estimate", "project", "issuetype", "reporter", "sprint", "team"\n  - **NOTE**: you must provide the exact wording for the above fields. Providing "user" instead of "assignee" will result in the assignee pivot not being used.\n- For visual grouping (always available): "fillcolor", "linecolor", "emojis", "tags"\n- For custom fields, use the exact field name from the data source\n- Standard fields are only available if the table\'s data source includes that field — if a field is unavailable, the tool returns an error listing valid options\n- Set a pivot field to "none" to remove that grouping\n- At least one pivot (row or column) must remain defined — both cannot be "none"\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot create a new dynamic table — use the appropriate creation tool for that\n- Cannot add or remove individual cards from the dynamic table\n- Cannot modify individual card properties — use *EditBlockCardData*, *EditBlockStyle*, or *EditTextArea* for that\n- Cannot create or update Jira sync configurations — use the SyncJiraToDynamicTable tool for that']};var UcbNk={Fe:UcDd.B2e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,lYb:!0,description:"## Role\n\nEdits structured data field values on integration-synced cards (e.g. ADO, Jira, or extension API cards).\nChanges are automatically synced back to the external system.\n\n## When to use\n\nUse when the user wants to modify any data field values on integration-synced cards — title, summary, status, assignee, priority, dates, description, custom fields, or any other field reported by ReadCardData.\nAlways call ReadCardData first to discover field names, current values, types, enum options, and locked status.\n\n## When NOT to use\n\nDo NOT use for visual properties — use *EditBlockStyle* (colors), *ResizeBlock* (size), *MoveBlock* (position), or *EditTextArea* (text styling) instead.\nDo NOT use for non-card shapes that have no data schema.\nDo NOT use for generic Lucid cards that are not synced with an external integration.\n\n## Field names\n\nUse the field `name` (not `label`) from ReadCardData output.\nFor enum fields, provide the display name string — the tool resolves it to the correct ID via the integration.\n\n## Locked fields\n\nReadCardData reports which fields are locked. Do not attempt to edit locked fields — the tool will skip them and report them as not editable.\n\n## Jira status fields\n\nThis tool cannot change the status field on Jira cards. Jira requires workflow transitions to change status, which this tool does not support. If the user asks to change a Jira card's status, let them know they need to change it manually via the status field on the card or in Jira directly."};var UccNk={Fe:UcDd.Dyd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nRewire or restyle a single endpoint (endpoint1 or endpoint2) of an existing line: connect to a new block, move to an absolute position, or change the endpoint style (arrow shape).\n\n## When to Use\n- Reconnecting one end of a line to a different block.\n- Pinning one end of a line to a specific (x, y) canvas position.\n- Changing the arrow style at one end of a line.\n- Any combination of the above in a single call — e.g. rewiring to a block while also changing the arrow style.\n\n## Rules\n- Endpoint must be "endpoint1" or "endpoint2".\n- Provide BlockId (with optional LinkX/LinkY) OR both X and Y to change geometry. Style can be provided on its own or together with a geometry change.\n- Emit one call per endpoint. To move both endpoints, emit two parallel tool calls.'};var UcdNk={Fe:UcDd.Eyd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nSet a single LineStyle property on one existing line: LineColor, LineWidth, StrokeStyle, or LineShape.\n\n## When to Use\n- Recoloring a connector.\n- Changing a connector's width, stroke pattern (solid/dashed/dotted), or routed shape.\n\n## Rules\n- Emit one call per (line, style) pair. To set multiple styles on a line, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- Value formatting follows LineStyle: hex for LineColor, numeric string for LineWidth, enum string for StrokeStyle and LineShape.\n- If you plan to reroute a specific non-elbow line with Manhattan routing, set LineShape to elbow first. Do not do this for lines that are intentionally straight/diagonal (for example, fishbone ribs)."};var UceNk={Fe:UcDd.K2c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nEdit a single text area on either a block or a line (connector label). Supports updating the text, alignment (blocks only), and character/whole-text formatting.\n\n## When to Use\n- Changing the text inside a named text area on a block or line.\n- Bolding/italicizing/coloring text in an existing text area.\n- Setting text alignment (left/center/right/top/middle/bottom) on a block's text area.\n\n## Rules\n- textAlign/textVAlign apply only to blocks and are ignored when the target is a line.\n- Emit one call per (itemId, textAreaName). To edit multiple text areas, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n\n## Finding the right TextArea name\n\nEach shape can have a number of TextAreas on it, each with a name and a value.  You are FORBIDDEN FROM GUESSING TEXT\nAREA NAMES.  You MUST get correct text area names by using the ShapeDetails tool on the shape class in question or by\nreading the LymTex of a similar shape to get a FULL PICTURE of what kinds of text areas exist."};var UcfNk={Fe:UcDd.D2e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to modify the settings of an existing Lucid timeline after it has been created.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The timeline must already exist — use the generatorId returned by the CreateLucidTimeline tool.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Change the timeline\'s date range (start date, end date, or both)\n- Change the timeline unit (days, weeks, sprints, months, or quarter)\n- Enable or disable capacity planning\n- Set a uniform capacity value for all time periods (e.g., story points per sprint)\n- Toggle weekend highlighting\n- Toggle the today marker\n- Map data fields from imported items (e.g., Jira issues) to the timeline\'s start and end dates\n- Configure row grouping (e.g., group by assignee, status, priority, or a custom field)\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId returned by the CreateLucidTimeline tool\n- Only provide the fields you want to change — leave other fields as empty strings\n- If changing dates, provide them in ISO 8601 format (YYYY-MM-DD)\n- Enabling capacity planning will automatically switch the unit from days to weeks if currently set to days\n- To set capacity values, capacity planning must be enabled first — if not already enabled, set EnableCapacityPlanning to "true" in the same call\n- For date field mapping, use the exact field name from the imported data source (e.g., "Start date", "Due date" for Jira fields)\n- Date field mapping should be done AFTER importing items onto the timeline with the SyncJiraToTimeline tool\n- If the field name is not found, the tool will return an error listing the available field names\n- For row grouping, use semantic names like "user", "status", "priority" for standard fields, or exact field names for custom fields\n- Set RowGroupByField to "none" to remove row grouping\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot create a new timeline — use CreateLucidTimeline for that\n- Cannot add or remove items from the timeline — use SyncJiraToTimeline for importing Jira issues\n- Cannot change the cards that are on the timeline']};var UcgNk={Fe:UcDd.L2e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nExports and downloads the current document as a file. When called, it triggers a browser download of the document.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The user asks to **download, export, or save** their document as a file\n- The user wants a **PDF or image** copy of their work\n- Examples: "Download this as a PDF", "Export my document", "Save this as a PNG"\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- The user wants to **print**\n- The user wants to **share** the document with others (different workflow)\n- The user wants to **save changes** (changes are auto-saved)\n\n## Important Notes\n\n- Triggers an **immediate browser download** — the user will see a file download in their browser\n- The download includes **all pages** in the document'};var UchNk={Fe:UcDd.pR,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nSearches for available product features and shows the user clickable buttons to activate them.\n\n## When to Use\n- The user asks you to do something in the product and no other tool can accomplish it directly\n- The user is looking for a specific feature, setting, or capability\n- Use this BEFORE HelpCenterFallback when the request is about a product feature (not a conceptual question)\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- You have a more specific tool that directly accomplishes the user's request (e.g., use GenerateDiagram for diagram creation)\n- The user is asking a conceptual question about how something works (use HelpCenterFallback instead)\n\n## How to use\n- Each query of `queries` is a fuzzy search that should be treated like a search box\n- It will return buttons, toggles, and menu items\n- Keep queries short; longer queries tend to fuzzy match on fewer results\n- Try to guess at what the feature might actually be called, as exact matches will be more likely to succeed\n- The user may request multiple things, in which case include several searches for each thing",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-features")};var UciNk={Fe:UcDd.X2e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"## Role\n\nThis is your primary way to *read* the canvas or document. It retrieves and filters context from the document, extracting only the items, properties, or entire diagrams that are relevant to the request.\n\n**IMPORTANT:** This tool is *not* for generating summaries or interpretations. It solely filters and returns raw context with no added commentary.\n\n## How It Works\n\n- Searches across the **entire document** for items matching criteria (e.g., by color, tags, text alignment, shape type, notes)\n- Can return **specific items** along with only the properties that were requested\n- Can declare an **entire diagram** as relevant when every part of it matches\n- Use **plain language** in selectionCriteria — the tool translates your instructions into filters internally\n\nThink of this as telling the assistant *what to pull out of the canvas so other tools can work with it*.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-reading-canvas")};var UcjNk={Fe:UcDd.Z9f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"## Role\n\nThis tool finds an available (non-overlapping) rectangular area on the current page of the canvas. Given a desired width and height and a position to search near, it returns the top-left coordinates of a clear area as close to that position as possible.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- **Before generating a new diagram** when other content already exists on the canvas, to avoid overlapping existing diagrams.\n- **When placing multiple diagrams** on the same page — call this tool for each subsequent diagram to find a clear area near the previous one.\n- **When the user asks to add content** near a specific location but you need to avoid collisions with existing blocks.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- When the canvas is empty — just place content wherever makes sense.\n- When editing existing blocks — use *MoveBlock*, *ResizeBlock*, *EditBlockStyle*, *EditTextArea*, or another Edit* sub-tool instead.\n- When you only need to read what is on the canvas — use *CanvasQuery*.\n\n## How It Works\n\nThe tool searches outward from the specified (NearX, NearY) position to find the closest rectangular area of the requested size that does not overlap any existing canvas items. A margin is applied around existing items to ensure spacing. You can optionally specify a preferred direction to search in.\n"};var UckNk={Fe:UcDd.AGc,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nGenerates ideas and adds them to the canvas as a **new grid of sticky notes**.\n\n## What This Tool Does\n\n- Creates a **fresh set of ideas** as individual sticky notes arranged in a grid\n- Can generate ideas based on a **user prompt** or **selected items** on the canvas\n- Output is always **sticky notes**, not diagram nodes or connected shapes\n- Defaults to 9 ideas; if the user requests a different number, convey that in the prompt\n\n## When to Use\n\n- User wants to **brainstorm ideas as sticky notes**\n- Creating a **new collection of ideas** independent of existing diagram structures\n- User explicitly asks for **sticky notes or a brainstorming grid**\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- **Do not use** if the user wants to add content to an **existing diagram** (flowchart, mindmap, ERD, etc.)\n- If the user has a mindmap and asks to "add ideas to the mindmap" → use *Generate Diagram* instead (they want to edit the diagram structure, not create sticky notes)\n- If the user mentions **editing, updating, expanding, or adding** to an existing diagram → use *Generate Diagram* regardless of words like "ideas" or "brainstorm"\n- If there is any **existing diagram** on the canvas that the user is referencing → default to *Generate Diagram*\n\n## Key Principle\n\nWords like "ideas" or "brainstorm" do **not** automatically mean this tool. Check context:\n- **Existing diagram** being edited? → Use *Generate Diagram*\n- **New standalone sticky notes**? → Use *this tool*\n',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-ideas")};var UclNk={Fe:UcDd.k3e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!1,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-diagram"),description:'**Generate Process Diagram Tool**\n\nBuilds the complete process-diagram composition — the diagram, its key, its outline (SOP), and the header — and\narranges them as one cohesive layout next to the process context frame.\n\n**When to Use:**\n- The context the user provided is a business-specific process, organizational workflow, or SOP that is specific to the user\'s business (not general public knowledge)\n- The user asks to build or generate process documentation.\n- The user asks to regenerate the process diagram or change what it depicts (e.g. add or remove a step, change the\n  flow).\n\n**When NOT to Use:**\n- The user asks to diagram a general process that is well-known public or general knowledge.\n- The user asks to diagram something that is not a process, workflow, or SOP — e.g., a system architecture diagram, a flowchart of a general concept, or a mindmap of ideas. Use the regular Generate Diagram tool for those.\n- For a change scoped to a single existing component that does not change the diagram — rewording, rewriting, or even\n  "regenerating" the SOP / outline, renaming the header, editing a single shape\'s label — use the in-place edit tools\n  instead. "Regenerate the SOP / key / header" on its own is a single-component edit, not a use of this tool. Only reach\n  for this tool when the diagram itself (its steps, flow, or lanes) is being (re)generated.\n\n**Key Behaviors:**\n- **Flowcharts and swimlanes** are the main supported process diagram types.\n- The diagram is the source the header, key and outline title are derived from. Every call regenerates the diagram and\n  then refreshes the header, key and outline from it, so they never drift out of sync with the diagram.\n- This tool **cannot edit** existing diagrams. Use the edit in place tools for that.\n- Re-running arranges the same layout frame in place rather than creating a new one, reuses the existing diagram\n  container so a regenerated diagram replaces the old one, and replaces the previous key / outline / header rather than\n  leaving duplicates behind.\n\n**Clarifying Questions:**\n- If the tool does not have enough information, it responds with a **clarifying question** instead of generating the composition.\n- Check the `wasDiagramGenerated` field on the result:\n  - `true` — the diagram and its derived components (key, outline, header) were generated\n  - `false` — nothing was generated; a clarifying question was returned in `clarifyingQuestion` instead\n- When a clarifying question was returned, **relay it to the user** (do not treat it as a failure), then wait for their answer before retrying.\n\n**Disconnected Components:**\n- The result may warn that the generated diagram contains disconnected components.\n- When it does, **immediately call this tool again** with an updated `diagram` description that depicts the **same process** but ensures every decision branch explicitly reconnects to the main flow or reaches End.\n- Do **not** message the user about the connectivity issue — **regenerate silently** so the user only sees the corrected diagram.\n'};var UcmNk={Fe:UcDd.n3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:["## Role\n\nRetrieves every screen-capture frame that falls inside one or more time windows of the active\nrecording so the assistant can batch-import images aligned with what was being said in the\ntranscript and choose the most informative frame(s) itself.\n\n## Capabilities\n\n- **Window-based retrieval** — returns every frame whose timestamp lies inside the inclusive\n  `[startSeconds, endSeconds]` interval of each supplied range\n- **Batch retrieval** — multiple ranges can be supplied in one call; results are concatenated in\n  the order the ranges were requested\n\n## Parameters\n\n- **ranges** — array of `{startSeconds, endSeconds}` time windows (in seconds, relative to the\n  start of the recording, excluding paused time). Pull the values from the transcript.\n\n**Window sizing:** Strongly prefer **short windows of 1-3 seconds** that yield a handful of\nframes. Long windows (more than 5 seconds) return many redundant frames, dilute the signal, and\nwaste tokens — split the moment into multiple short ranges instead of one wide one.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The conversation contains a timestamped transcript and you need the visuals around specific\n  moments\n- You are producing a process diagram or summary that benefits from selective frames rather than\n  the full frame set — let the tool return all frames inside the window so you can pick the best\n  one(s) yourself\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- There is no recording associated with this conversation\n- A snapshot of the current canvas is needed — use *GetScreenshot* instead"]};var UcnNk={Fe:UcDd.Tyd,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nRetrieves the available line connection points for one or more blocks on the canvas. Connection points are the specific positions where lines can attach to a shape.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Before creating or rewiring lines with `CreateLine` or `EditLineEndpoint` when connecting to ERD entity shapes or other shapes with dynamic, per-field connection points\n- When you need to know exactly where lines can attach to a shape (e.g., which side, which row/field)\n- When connecting to shapes that have more than the standard 4 connection points (top, bottom, left, right)\n\n## What It Returns\n\nFor each block, returns an array of connection points with:\n- `x` / `y`: Normalized coordinates (0.0–1.0) that can be passed directly as `LinkX` / `LinkY` to `CreateLine` or `EditLineEndpoint`\n- `description`: Human-readable description of what the point connects to (e.g., "left: user_id (field 2)")\n\n## Standard Shapes\n\nMost shapes have 4 connection points at the midpoints of each edge. You do not need to call this tool for standard shapes — just use `LinkX=0`/`LinkY=0.5` (left), `LinkX=1`/`LinkY=0.5` (right), `LinkX=0.5`/`LinkY=0` (top), `LinkX=0.5`/`LinkY=1` (bottom).\n\n## ERD Entities\n\nERD entity shapes have dynamic connection points — one pair (left + right) per field/row. Use this tool to discover the exact `LinkY` value for each field before creating lines.'};var UcoNk={Fe:UcDd.Sbe,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nReturns the full details of the document\'s currently active theme — palette (primary, accent, neutral/background colors), font family/families, and any other styling properties the document carries. Also reports the theme\'s name (`themeName`) and whether the document is on the built-in default theme (`isDefaultTheme`).\n\n## When to use\n- When the user asks **about** the document\'s theme or styling (e.g. "what\'s the theme of this document?", "what fonts/colors is it using?"). Call this tool, then summarize the result for the user. The theme exists even when the canvas is empty, so an empty document is not a reason to skip the call.\n- Before creating new content or restyling existing content to match the document\'s visual style, when the user did **not** specify colors, fonts, or styling.\n\n## When NOT to use\n- The user has given explicit styling instructions (e.g. "make these red", "use Comic Sans"). Honor the user directly instead.\n- No new visual content is being created or restyled.\n\n## Notes\n- Call at most once per turn. The theme does not change mid-turn.\n- When `isDefaultTheme` is true, the user has not deliberately chosen a palette, so you have latitude to pick tasteful colors for new content. When it is false, the user picked a specific theme (named in `themeName`) — match its palette and fonts closely rather than introducing your own.'};var UcpNk={Fe:UcDd.s3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:['## Role\n\nCaptures a visual screenshot of the document/canvas for vision-based analysis. Use this tool when you need to understand visual properties that are not captured by text-based tools like FilterCanvas.\n\n## Capabilities\n\n- **Visual layout** and spatial relationships between shapes\n- **Colors, sizes, and positioning** of elements\n- **Overall diagram structure** and organization\n- **Alignment and spacing** issues\n\n## Parameters\n\n- **captureScope** — What to capture (*Viewport*, *FullPage*, or *Selection*)\n- **includeBackground** — Whether to include the page background\n\n## When to Use\n\n- User asks about **visual appearance** ("What does this look like?")\n- User asks about **layout** ("Are these aligned?")\n- User asks about **colors or styling** ("What color is this shape?")\n- You need to **verify spatial relationships** before making changes\n- You want to **understand visual context** before answering questions\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- For **text content analysis** — use FilterCanvas instead\n- For **semantic structure** — use FilterCanvas instead\n- When shape properties are **already known** from previous tools\n\n## Example Scenarios\n\n- "Show me what the canvas looks like" → Use GetScreenshot with *Viewport* scope\n- "Are these shapes aligned properly?" → Use GetScreenshot then analyze positioning\n- "What\'s the layout of this section?" → Use GetScreenshot to see spatial arrangement']};var UcqNk={Fe:UcDd.w1b,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"## Role\n\nSearches the Lucid Help Center articles for information that the user may find helpful.  You are NOT TO USE THIS TOOL to look for assistance in completing your tasks, or for any other purpose.  The ONLY VALID USE OF THIS TOOL IS when you are absolutely certain that there is no tool or skill that can enable you to complete the user's request, and you have already used the FeatureFind tool to look for other options the user could take.\n\nIt is ABSOLUTELY FORBIDDEN for you to use this tool to learn how to accomplish a task; use the existing system prompts, tools, and skills (if any) to learn how to complete your tasks.\nIt is also ABSOLUTELY FORBIDDEN for you to consult this tool to learn how to accomplish tasks that you don't think you have the tools for.\n\n## Result\n\nWhen you call this tool, it will result in a few suggested articles being shown to the user pertaining to your query. This can be helpful when the user has a question about the product that you cannot answer yourself.  Again, this is NOT meant to be a tool where YOU can gain information about how to accomplish tasks; it is to inform the user about the product more generally.\n\n",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-helpdesk")};var UcrNk={Fe:UcDd.gbg,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-documents"),description:["## Role\nSearch the user's Lucid documents using structured, typed criteria and return matching documents with enough context for the user to recognize them.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Provide one or more text criteria, each targeting the title, the content, or both. Matching is typo-tolerant and rewards consecutive-word matches. Multiple criteria are combined with OR and drive relevance ranking.\n- Filter by last-modified and created date ranges, by owner user IDs, by collaborator user IDs and group IDs (who the document is shared with), and by status.\n- Combine any subset: filters AND together; text criteria rank within the filtered set.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Choose each criterion's target by what the user remembers: use 'title' for a remembered name (typo-tolerant, and consecutive-word matches rank highest), 'content' for what is inside the document (broader and stemmed, but no typo tolerance), or 'title_and_content' when unsure.\n- Provide dates as absolute ISO-8601 timestamps; resolve relative phrases like \"yesterday\" to absolute values before calling.\n- Owner and collaborator fields take numeric user/group IDs and describe OTHER people on the document the user is looking for. Resolve any names to IDs first; never invent IDs. Results are always already limited to documents the calling user can access — these fields do not change that.\n- For ambiguous \"X or Y\" recall, prefer issuing separate searches and comparing the results rather than forcing both into one criterion.\n\n## Limitations\n- Lexical matching only (keyword / fuzzy / phrase); it does NOT do semantic or embedding-based topic similarity.\n- It cannot create, edit, share, rename, or delete documents.\n- It only returns documents the calling user already has access to.\n- You do not control how many results come back. The tool returns the most relevant matches, ranked by relevance, and is not guaranteed to be exhaustive. If the user is looking for something specific that is missing, refine the criteria and search again rather than asking for \"more\" results.\n\n## Exclusion Rules\n- Do not call this tool with no text criteria and no filters — that returns an undifferentiated dump. If nothing is implied, ask a clarifying question first.\n- Do not call this tool when the user wants to modify a document."]};var UcsNk={Fe:UcDd.t4e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,lYb:!0,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-jira"),description:["## Role\nUse this tool to search for Jira issues using a JQL (Jira Query Language) query and return relevant information about the matching issues.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Execute JQL queries against the user's connected Jira instance\n- Return issue keys, summaries, statuses, assignees, priorities, and other fields\n- Validate that a JQL query returns the expected set of issues before using it for timeline creation\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Build the JQL query from details the user provides (project name, team, sprint, labels, etc.)\n- **Narrate the query to the user in plain English** when confirming it (e.g. \"I'll pull open issues in the Mobile project for the current sprint\"). Do not show raw JQL syntax in user-facing messages unless the user has shown they read JQL.\n- After receiving results, summarize what was found and confirm with the user that these are the correct issues\n- If the results don't match expectations, iterate on the JQL query — adjust filters, add or remove conditions\n- Keep queries focused: avoid overly broad queries that return hundreds of irrelevant issues\n- **Before the first call in a conversation**, if the user is not already connected to Jira, send a one-paragraph preamble explaining that Lucid will read the named fields, that the connection is read-only (Lucid will not modify Jira issues), and why the access is needed for what they asked. This eases the \"Allow access\" anxiety users have at the auth step.\n\n## Limitations\n- Cannot modify Jira issues — this tool is read-only\n- Requires a valid Jira connection (authentication is triggered automatically if needed)\n- Results are limited to the fields available in the user's Jira instance"]};var UctNk={Fe:UcDd.G6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"## Role\nUse this tool to compute optimal X/Y positions for blocks in entity-relationship diagrams before placing them on the canvas.\n\n## When to Use\n- When creating an entity-relationship diagram (ERD) with tables/entities and their relationships\n- When connections between blocks are bidirectional and minimizing line crossings matters\n- When you want a clean layout optimized for readability of relationships\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- For directed flowcharts or process diagrams — use RecommendSugiyamaLayout instead\n- For simple grid arrangements with no connections — use RecommendGridLayout instead\n- For single blocks or very simple 2-3 block diagrams where manual placement is trivial\n\n## How to Use\n1. Plan all your blocks (assign each a unique ID and label) and connections\n2. Call this tool with the full list of blocks and connections\n3. The tool returns computed X/Y pixel coordinates for each block\n4. Use those coordinates to place or edit block positions on the canvas\n\n## Grid and Spacing\n- You can adjust spacing by providing a LayoutGrid parameter with custom block sizes and spacing.\n- If unsure or unspecified by the user, use the recommended default values.\n\n## Connections\n- Connections are treated as bidirectional for layout purposes\n- The algorithm optimizes to minimize line crossings between connected blocks"};var UcuNk={Fe:UcDd.H6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"## Role\nUse this tool to compute X/Y positions for diagram blocks arranged in a uniform grid before placing them on the canvas.\n\n## When to Use\n- When arranging blocks in a grid pattern (e.g., comparison tables, card layouts, icon grids)\n- When the blocks have no directional connections or hierarchy\n- When you want evenly spaced rows and columns\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- When blocks have directed connections or flow — use RecommendSugiyamaLayout instead\n- For single blocks or 2-3 block diagrams where manual placement is trivial\n- When editing existing diagrams where blocks are already placed\n\n## How to Use\n1. Plan all your blocks (assign each a unique ID and label)\n2. Optionally specify the number of columns; if omitted, an approximately square grid is used\n3. Call this tool with the list of blocks\n4. The tool returns computed X/Y pixel coordinates for each block\n5. Use those coordinates to place or edit block positions on the canvas\n\n## Grid and Spacing\n- You can adjust spacing by providing a LayoutGrid parameter with custom block sizes and spacing.\n- If unsure or unspecified by the user, use the recommended default values.\n\n## Columns\n- Set the Columns parameter to control how many blocks appear per row\n- If omitted, the grid will be approximately square (e.g., 9 blocks → 3x3)"};var UcvNk={Fe:UcDd.I6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\nUse this tool to compute optimal X/Y positions for diagram blocks before placing them on the canvas.\n\n## When to Use\n- Before placing blocks when creating a diagram with 4 or more connected blocks\n- When you want a clean, professional layout without manually computing coordinates\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- For single blocks or very simple 2-3 block diagrams where manual placement is trivial\n- When editing existing diagrams where blocks are already placed\n\n## How to Use\n1. Plan all your blocks (assign each a unique ID and label) and connections\n2. Call this tool with the full list of blocks and connections\n3. The tool returns computed X/Y pixel coordinates for each block\n4. Use those coordinates to place or edit block positions on the canvas\n\n## Grid and Spacing\n- You can adjust spacing by providing a LayoutGrid parameter with custom block sizes and spacing.\n- If unsure or unspecified by the user, use the recommended default values.\n\n## Direction\n- "horizontal" (default): left-to-right flow, best for flowcharts and process diagrams\n- "vertical": top-to-bottom flow, best for org charts and hierarchical diagrams\n\n## Handling Cycles\n- If the diagram has cycles, provide StartBlockId and/or EndBlockId to anchor the layout\n- StartBlockId places that block at the beginning (leftmost or topmost)\n- EndBlockId places that block at the end (rightmost or bottommost)'};var UcwNk={Fe:UcDd.WGc,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"## Role\n\nLoads a skill into your active context. The skill's content becomes available to you and any tools attached to the skill become callable on subsequent waves.\n\n## When to Use\n\nUse this tool once you have identified a relevant skill in the **Available Skills** section of your system prompt and you intend to act on the user's request using that skill's guidance and tools.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- To \"preview\" a skill you are unsure about. The skill content is delivered immediately on load; there is no separate preview step.\n- For a skill you already have loaded.\n\n## Important Notes\n\n- Pass the exact skill `name` from the **Available Skills** list. Names are case-sensitive.\n- If the skill name does not match a registered skill, the call fails — re-check the **Available Skills** list for the correct name."};var UcxNk={Fe:UcDd.B3c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nReposition and/or rotate a single existing block on the canvas.\n\n## When to Use\n- Repositioning a block (absolute X/Y)\n- Moving a block in front of or behind another block\n- Rotating a block\n\n## Rules\n- To change a block's size, use ResizeBlock.\n- Emit one call per block. To move multiple blocks, emit multiple parallel tool calls."};var UcyNk={Fe:UcDd.s5e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nMove a single existing block to a specific cell of an assisted-layout container. Block identity is preserved — the moved block keeps its id along with all connected lines, comments, and external references.\n\nHandles two cases under one schema:\n- **Within-grid repositioning** — block is already in the target container\'s grid; reposition to a new cell (including across subsections of a multi-subsection container, e.g. across lanes of the same swimlane).\n- **Into-grid relocation** — block is on the free canvas or in a different grid; move it into the target container at the specified cell.\n\n## When to Use\n- Moving a block between cells of an assisted-layout container, or between subsections of a multi-subsection container (e.g. between lanes of a swimlane).\n- Relocating a free-canvas block into an assisted-layout grid.\n- Moving a block from one assisted-layout container to another.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Free-canvas → free-canvas moves (no grid involved) → use *MoveBlock* with X/Y or DeltaX/DeltaY.\n- Duplicating a block at a new location → use *CopyPasteItems*.\n\n## Rules\n- **Finding `Placement.ContainerId`**: use the container-tree view\'s `containerId` on a node with `assistedLayoutEnabled: true`. NOT a synthetic lane entry id like `<id>-1` (those appear in the flowchart view for multi-subsection containers as a rendering artifact, not as addressable containers).\n- `"swapPositions"` (Placement.ToolCollisionHandlingPreference) requires the block to already reside in the same container.\n- Emit one call per block. To move multiple blocks, emit parallel tool calls.\n- Connected lines follow the block automatically — do NOT pre-emptively call *EditLineEndpoint* unless the move also reroutes the logical flow.\n\n## Subsection switches\n\nMulti-subsection containers number indices **per-subsection** on the subsection\'s axis, but share the other axis across all subsections of that type:\n\n- Row-subsections (horizontal lanes): rows are per-lane, columns are shared.\n- Column-subsections (vertical bands): columns are per-band, rows are shared.\n\n**Rule:** pass coordinates that exist in the destination subsection\'s view of the grid.\n\n- **Shared axis**: carry the source/reference block\'s index — it transfers cleanly across subsections.\n- **Per-subsection axis**: pass only when you have a reference block sitting in the *destination* subsection (e.g., "below Sign-off Granted? in the Stakeholder lane"). Otherwise **omit** — defaults to 1.\n\n**Same-subsection case:** when `SubsectionId` points to the source\'s own subsection, no boundary is crossed — carry both `Row` and `Column` from the source/reference block.\n\n**How to find the SubsectionId:** in *CanvasQuery*\'s flowchart view, each lane is a top-level node carrying `label` and **either** `rowSubsectionId` **or** `columnSubsectionId`. Match by `label`, copy the present field verbatim into the matching `Placement.RowSubsectionId` / `Placement.ColumnSubsectionId`. The *presence* of `rowSubsectionId` vs `columnSubsectionId` tells you which axis the lane lives on.\n\nExample — pure lane switch (user names a destination lane, no positional reference):\n```\n{ItemId: "<block-id>", Placement: {ContainerId: "<container-id>", RowSubsectionId: "<dest-rowSubsectionId>", Column: <source-column>}}\n```\nSource column carried (shared axis). `Row` omitted — defaults to row 1 of the destination lane.\n\nExample — same-subsection relative placement (user names a positional reference block in the same lane):\n```\n{ItemId: "<block-id>", Placement: {ContainerId: "<container-id>", RowSubsectionId: "<same-rowSubsectionId>", Row: <ref-row>, Column: <ref-column + 1>}}\n```\nBoth axes carried from the reference block; the column axis is adjusted by 1 to land in the next cell. No boundary is crossed, so per-subsection numbering doesn\'t apply.\n\nExample — cross-subsection with a destination-side row reference (user names both a destination lane and a reference block already in it):\n```\n{ItemId: "<block-id>", Placement: {ContainerId: "<container-id>", RowSubsectionId: "<dest-rowSubsectionId>", Row: <dest-ref-row + 1>, Column: <source-column>}}\n```\n`Row` computed relative to the destination-side reference (per CanvasQuery\'s view of the destination lane). `Column` carried from source (shared axis).'};var UczNk={Fe:UcDd.ifg,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!0,description:'## Role\nOpens the existing Add to repository flow so the user can move or publish the current diagram/document to a repository.\n\n## When to use\n- The user asks to move, add, publish, or save this process diagram/document to a repository.\n- The user clicks a "Move to repository" suggested action.\n\n## Behavior\n- This tool only opens the normal repository UI.\n- Do not choose a destination repository yourself.\n- If the repository flow is unavailable for the current user or document, tell the user the action is not available.'};var UcANk={Fe:UcDd.E6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\n\nList the AI suggestions currently on the canvas, each with its anchor item ID, type, status, title, and description.\n\n## When to Use\n- Before *CreateAiSuggestions*, to avoid creating a duplicate suggestion for an item that already has one.\n- Before *UpdateAiSuggestions* or *ResolveAiSuggestions*, to confirm the item ID has an active suggestion and its current state.\n- Whenever you need to reason about outstanding suggestions before acting on the canvas.\n\n## Output\n- Returns one entry per suggestion with its item ID, type, status, title, and description.\n- Lists only suggestions still on the canvas; resolved suggestions are not included.\n- Returns an explicit "no suggestions" message when the canvas has none.'};var UcBNk={Fe:UcDd.iig,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"## Role\n\nReturns structured data fields (label, value, type, enum options) for the specified Lucid cards.\n\n## When to use\n\nUse this tool when you already have card IDs and need their structured data fields.\nCard IDs come from CanvasQuery, FilterCanvas, or the user's selection context.\n\n## When NOT to use\n\nDo NOT use this tool to find cards. Use CanvasQuery instead to search by text, color, shape type, or region.\n\n## Pagination\n\nResults are paginated. By default, up to 50 cards are returned per call.\nUse the Offset and Limit parameters to paginate through larger sets.\nThe response indicates when more results are available.\n\n## Output\n\nFor each card, returns:\n- A list of fields with: label (human-readable name), value, type (string/number/date/boolean/color/etc.), enum options if applicable, and locked status.\n- Integration info showing which external integration (e.g. jira_cloud, extension_api) the card is synced to."};var UcCNk={Fe:UcDd.e4c,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,Nvb:!1,description:"## Role\n\nOutputs the current process context frame content: attached files, chat notes (recorded Q&A decisions), and diagram status.\n\n## File Content\n\nPDFs and images are returned as binary attachments on the result; all other files are returned inline as parsed text.\n\n## Deduping\n\nTo avoid re-sending content already in the conversation, a file may be referenced instead of re-output. A reference means the content is **already available above** — find and use it there; do not assume it is missing or re-read it. Look for:\n\n- `Note: present in conversation history (ref: {interactionId}_{fileIndex})` — the file was uploaded earlier; locate it by its `[File Reference: ...]`.\n- `Note: already provided by an earlier read_process_context_frame call (ref: {toolCallId})` — the content was returned by an earlier call to this tool; locate it in that tool's result.\n"};var UcDNk={Fe:UcDd.Bee,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nRenames the current document.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The user asks to **rename**, **retitle**, or **change the name/title** of the document\n- Examples: 'Rename this doc to Q3 Planning', 'Change the title to Roadmap', 'Call this Sprint Retrospective'\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- The user wants to rename a page, frame, or other item on the canvas (this tool only renames the whole document)\n- The user wants to rename a shape or block\n\n## Important Notes\n\n- Leading and trailing whitespace is trimmed\n- A rename with the same (trimmed) title as the current one is a no-op and is treated as success\n- An empty (trimmed) title is rejected"};var UcENk={Fe:UcDd.sig,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"**Render Tool**: Captures a PNG screenshot of the document so you can visually inspect it.\n\nBy default it renders the entire current page. Provide item IDs to crop the screenshot to the bounding box around just those blocks/lines.\n\n**When to use:**\n- To see what the document actually looks like (layout, alignment, spacing, colors, overall structure).\n- To verify the visual result after modifying the document.\n\n**When NOT to use:**\n- To read structured data (IDs, text, properties) — use the Run Script tool instead; rendered text may be too small to read reliably.\n\n**Notes:**\n- The render is the source of truth for what a document looks like. It is exactly what the user can see."};var UcFNk={Fe:UcDd.yig,qj:!0,Vj:new Ucyhi,description:'## Role\nOpens the unlock-access flow so the user can request unlock access flow.\nDepending on the user\'s state this either opens the request-edit-access dialog or triggers the license-request flow with a dialog.\n\n## When to use\nCall this tool when the user explicitly asks to request edit access, request a license, or unlock access to the document.\nExamples: "Request edit access", "Unlock access", "How do I get edit access?", "Request a license", "Can I get a license?"\n\n## Important\n- Only call this tool when the user has directly indicated they want to request access.\n- Do not call this tool proactively — wait for the user to ask.\n\n## After execution — how to respond\nThe tool result will tell you which flow was triggered. Use that to guide your MessageUser response:\n- **License request flow**: Tell the user the license request dialog has opened. Use language like "unlock access" or "request a license" — do NOT say "request edit access".\n- **Edit access request flow**: Tell the user the modal to request edit access from the document owner has opened.'};var UcGNk={Fe:UcDd.j4c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nReroutes existing elbow lines around blocks using Manhattan grid routing to create cleaner, more direct orthogonal paths with fewer unnecessary bends.\n\n## Parameters\n- **`BlockIds`** — IDs of all blocks in the diagram. Used as routing obstacles; the router needs the full set to avoid routing lines through blocks they shouldn't cross. Always pass all blocks, not just the ones connected to the lines being rerouted.\n- **`LineIds`** (optional) — IDs of specific lines to reroute. Omit to reroute all lines connected to the blocks in `BlockIds`. Use this to limit changes after editing a single block or rewiring one line.\n\n## Limitations\n- **Cyclical lines skipped** — lines with cyclical shape cannot be routed and are excluded\n- **Elbow routing only** — Manhattan rerouting is orthogonal/elbow-style. For a non-elbow line, set line shape to elbow first only when orthogonal rerouting is intended.\n- **Preserve intended geometry** — if a line is intentionally straight or diagonal (for example, fishbone ribs), do not convert it to elbow just to reroute.\n\n## Result\nReturns a `## Results` section with one bullet per outcome:\n- Count of line IDs successfully rerouted\n- All cyclical line IDs in a single bullet (if any)\n- Non-elbow line IDs skipped with their original shape (if any)"};var UcHNk={Fe:UcDd.k4c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nResize a single block's overall width and height (absolute pixel values or deltas).\n\n## When to Use\n- Changing a block's overall width or height, absolutely or by a delta.\n\n## Rules\n- Width/Height are absolute pixel values; DeltaWidth/DeltaHeight are pixel changes. If both are supplied on the same axis the delta wins.\n- Emit one call per block. To resize multiple blocks, emit multiple parallel tool calls.\n- To resize internal parts of a block (e.g. table cells), fetch the shape's details to determine the appropriate controls."};var UcINk={Fe:UcDd.R6e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nResolve one or more AI suggestions currently on the canvas. Each entry marks a single suggestion as\neither **accepted** (the change was applied) or **ignored** (dismissed without action). Each resolved\nsuggestion's callout is hidden afterward.\n\n## When to Use\n- A **recommendation** suggestion's change has been applied — resolve it as **accepted**.\n- The user has indicated a suggestion is no longer relevant or declines to act on it — resolve it as **ignored**.\n- A **contextNeeded** suggestion has been answered **and** the answer truly maps to no useful change — resolve it as **accepted**. Otherwise, prefer *UpdateAiSuggestions*.\n- **Always call *ReadAiSuggestions* first** to confirm each suggestion is still open and get its **itemId** — its state may have changed since you last saw it.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- A **contextNeeded** suggestion has been answered and the answer suggests any refinement (label change, added note, item split, etc.) — use *UpdateAiSuggestions* to morph it into a recommendation first.\n- A suggestion you **just morphed from contextNeeded into a recommendation this same turn** — the user has not yet seen or accepted the new recommendation. Do not update and resolve in the same turn; wait for the user to explicitly accept before resolving. Answering a contextNeeded question is supplying context, not accepting a change.\n- A **recommendation** suggestion exists but has not been explicitly accepted and applied — wait; do not preemptively resolve.\n- To edit canvas items. This tool only updates suggestion status; it does not modify the canvas.\n- To create a suggestion. Use *CreateAiSuggestions* instead.\n- For item IDs that have no active suggestion in the *ReadAiSuggestions* results. Those entries are skipped."};var UcJNk={Fe:UcDd.Pig,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"Drive the document by running JavaScript snippets against the live page using the run_script_v2_skill"};var UcKNk={Fe:UcDd.o3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"This tool finds shapes on the canvas that are linked to semantic resources in a specific dataset, and returns their JSON representation.\n\n## When to Use\n- When the user asks about shapes on the canvas that are linked to semantic data — note: not all shapes are data-backed.\n- When you need shape IDs in order to act on (move, edit, select, etc) specific data-backed shapes\n- After querying resources via QuerySemanticResources, to find their corresponding shapes on the canvas\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Do not use to query resources in the semantic dataset itself — use QuerySemanticResources for that\n- Do not use if you only need resource data without needing the shapes\n- Not all shapes in the domain are data-backed. If you need to find shapes that are NOT linked to semantic resources, use CanvasQuery instead\n\n## Filters\n- `resourceTypes`: Return only shapes linked to resources of these types\n- `resourceIds`: Return only shapes linked to these specific resource IDs\n- If provided together, both filters are applied (AND logic)\n- Filters are required to prevent excessive results. If no filters are provided, the tool will return an error instructing you to provide at least one filter.\n\n## Warning\n- This tool enforces a result cap by default to prevent context bloating. If the cap is hit, the response will include a truncation warning instructing you to call again with `bypassCap` set to `true`, only use this if you are certain you need the full set.\n\n## Output\nA JSON representation of the matching canvas shapes, in the same format returned by CanvasQuery.\nShapes generated by a Cloud Frame (CloudVizGenerator) carry `belongsToCloudFrame: true`; the field is omitted for all other shapes."};var UcLNk={Fe:UcDd.q3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"This tool returns partial JSON schemas for each requested resource type in a semantic dataset.\nSchemas describe the shape of the data — which fields are available, their types, and how data points relate to each other.\nUse schemas to understand what fields you can filter or query on before calling QuerySemanticResources.\n\nThe returned schemas are filtered to include only the fields relevant to your schemasPrompt.\nThis keeps context concise for large resource types.\nIf you need fields that are not in the partial schema, call this tool again with a broader schemasPrompt.\n\n## When to Use\n- After knowing which resource types are relevant to the user's question, fetch their schemas to understand the available fields\n- After using QuerySemanticResourceTypes to find exact resource type names\n- Use this before forming a QuerySemanticResources call when you need to know what data is available\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Do not fetch all resource type schemas at once — only request schemas for the types relevant to the user's question\n- Skip this call if you already know the schema for the resource types you need\n\n## Parameters\n- datasetId (required): The ID of the semantic dataset containing the resource types.\n- resourceTypes (required): An array of resource type names to fetch schemas for. Resource types are in PascalCase and plural. The list of exact resource type strings can be obtained by calling GetResourceTypesForDataset.\n- schemasPrompt (required): A description of what information you need from the schemas. The more specific your prompt, the more focused the returned schema will be.\n\n## Output\nA partial JSON object mapping each requested resource type to its filtered JSON schema.\nOnly the fields relevant to your schemasPrompt are included.\nIf a schema is not found for a particular resource type, that will be indicated in the result."};var UcMNk={Fe:UcDd.r3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'This tool returns resource types from a specific semantic dataset that are relevant to what you are looking for.\n\n## Parameters\n- **datasetId**: The ID of the semantic dataset to query.\n- **resourceTypesPrompt**: A description of what resource types you are looking for. Only matching resource types from the dataset will be returned.\n\n## When to Use\n- Use this before fetching schemas or querying resources, to know what types are available and their names.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- You already called this tool for the dataset and have the resource types you need\n\n## Output\nA JSON array of resource types as strings matching your prompt, e.g.:\n`["type1", "type2", "type3"]`\n\nIf the dataset is not found or has no matching resource types, the result will say so.'};var UcNNk={Fe:UcDd.V$f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,RU:i18n.get("ai-agent-get-semantic-data-agent-for-query-loading"),description:'\nSpecialized expert agents are available for certain domains to answer questions, query third party data, and diagram with that data.\nThis tool analyzes the user\'s query against available agents and datasets and recommends the most relevant agent to switch to (if any) for domain expertise.\nIt does not automatically switch to that agent.\n\n## When to Use\n- Always use this tool when the user asks about cloud infrastructure or cloud diagramming (e.g., AWS, Azure, GCP)\n- Otherwise, when the user seems to be asking about domain-specific data that might be linked to the document.\n- It only takes a second to check for available agents, and the specialized agent will always do a better job at answering the user\'s question.\n- Before switching to a semantic data agent — call this first to confirm which agent and datasets are relevant\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- You are already inside a semantic data agent\n- The user\'s request does not pertain to domain-specific or cloud diagramming.\n\n## Output\nThe name of the recommended semantic data agent and the relevant dataset IDs, e.g.:\n`{ "recommendedAgentName": "aws_semantic_data_agent", "relevantDatasetIds": ["uuid-1", "uuid-2"] }`\n\nIf no data agent is applicable to the user\'s query, the response will be say so and the reason.\n\n## After This Tool\n- If a recommendedAgentName is returned, use the Switch Agent tool to hand off to that agent.\n- If no data is linked or no agent is applicable, use MessageUser to inform the user in plain language. Do not use technical terms like "semantic data agent" or "dataset" — say something like "It looks like there\'s no AWS data linked to this document yet."'};var UcONk={Fe:UcDd.X$f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'This tool returns the semantic dataset IDs present in the current document for a specific semantic domain. Given a domain key, it returns an array of semantic dataset IDs of that domain type.\n\n## When to Use\n- You know the DomainType the user is referring to and need the dataset IDs for that domain\n- Use this tool to discover dataset IDs for a specific domain before acting on them\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- You already know the specific dataset IDs the user is referring to — avoid redundant calls\n\n## Output\nAn array of dataset ID strings for the given domain, e.g.:\n`["uuid-1", "uuid-2"]`\n\nIf the document has no semantic data for the given domain, the result will say so.'};var UcPNk={Fe:UcDd.Y$f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,RU:i18n.get("ai-agent-get-semantic-datasets-for-query-loading"),description:'This tool finds the semantic datasets in the current document that are relevant to a natural-language query. It analyzes the query against every semantic domain present in the document and returns the dataset IDs for the domains that match.\n\n## When to Use\n- The user asks about data linked to the document but you don\'t yet know which domain or dataset IDs are relevant\n- You want to discover the relevant dataset IDs across all domains in a single step instead of guessing a domain key\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- You already know the specific dataset IDs the user is referring to — avoid redundant calls\n\n## Output\nA JSON object mapping each matched domain to its relevant dataset IDs, e.g.:\n`{"aws": ["uuid-1", "uuid-2"]}`\n\nIf the document has no semantic data, or no domain is relevant to the query, the result will say so.'};var UcQNk={Fe:UcDd.t3e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'This tool retrieves relation definitions that describe how resource types are structurally connected to each other in a dataset.\nEach relation has the form: { from: ResourceType, type: string, to: ResourceType }.\nUse this to understand data relationships before writing relational queries or constructing SPARQL queries.\n\n## When to Use\n- After you requested the available resource types in the dataset via GetResourceTypesForDataset\n- When you need to understand how resource types are connected before querying across multiple types\n- Before constructing a SPARQL query using QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql\n- When the user asks about relationships or connections between data types, including containment (e.g. resources within a region)\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Do not use this tool to retrieve actual resource instances — use QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql or QuerySemanticResources for that\n- Do not call this if you already know the relevant relation definitions from prior context in this session\n\n## Parameters\n- `resourceTypePairs`: Provide pairs of resource types to find all relations between those types.\n- `resourceTypes`: Provide a list of resource type names to find all their relations, including relationships with resources not in the list.\n- At least one of the two parameters must be provided.\n- DO NOT combine broad resourceTypes input with resourceTypePairs, as resources included in resourceTypes will make any resourceTypePair with that type redundant.\n\n## Considerations\n- **The `from`/`to` direction maps directly to SPARQL subject/object order:** in a relation `{from: "A", type: "R", to: "B"}`, `A` is the subject and `B` is the object. See QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql for the exact pattern.\n- All container resources have a single direct relationship to all contained resources, so resourceTypes: ["<ContainerType>"] will surface relationships to all contained resource types.\n- When asked about the relationship between two specific resource types, prefer providing those two types as a pair in resourceTypePairs to narrow down results and reduce context size.\n- When the user’s question is centered on one anchor resource type and you want to discover everything that type is related to, prefer passing that single type in resourceTypes.\n- Use resourceTypePairs when you already know the candidate related types you want to test and want tighter scope.\n- Use resourceTypes only with a small number of resource types to avoid large responses.\n\n## Output\nA JSON object keyed by the query (resource type name, or "TypeA <-> TypeB" for pairs).\n\nFor `resourceTypes` queries, the value is an array grouped by source resource type. Each entry has the form:\n```\n{\n    from: string; // the resource type the relations start from\n    relations: Array<{\n        type: string;     // the type of the relation\n        to: string[];     // resource types this relation points to\n    }>;\n}\n```\nMultiple entries appear when the queried type participates in relations as both source and target — there will be one entry per distinct `from`.\n\nFor `resourceTypePairs` queries, the value is a flat array of relation triplets, each of the form:\n```\n{\n    from: string; // the resource type the relation starts from\n    type: string; // the type of the relation\n    to: string;   // the resource type the relation points to\n}\n```\n\nExample output:\n```\n{\n    "Region": [\n        {\n            "from": "Region",\n            "relations": [\n                { "type": "hasDefined", "to": ["EC2", "Bucket", "Lambda"] },\n                { "type": "isRunning", "to": ["EC2Instance"] }\n            ]\n        },\n        {\n            "from": "Account",\n            "relations": [\n                { "type": "contains", "to": ["Region"] }\n            ]\n        }\n    ],\n    "ResourceType2 <-> ResourceType1": [\n        { "from": "ResourceType2", "type": "is part of", "to": "ResourceType1" }\n    ],\n    "ResourceType3": "No relationships found for resource type ResourceType3"\n};\n```\n'};var UcRNk={Fe:UcDd.w6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"This tool retrieves actual semantic resources from a dataset, with optional filters to narrow the results.\nUse this as a fallback if QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql is not available or returns no results.\n\n## When to Use\n- If you simply need to get a resource by name or id.\n- OR: you don't have access to QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql\n- OR: After attempting unsuccessfully to use QuerySemanticResourcesWithSparql\n- After determining which resource types are relevant (via GetResourceTypesForDataset) and optionally understanding their schemas (via GetResourceSchemasForDataset)\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Do not call without at least one filter — unfiltered queries on large datasets may return too many results and be unhelpful\n- Do not guess field names or filters without consulting the schema first\n\n## Warning\n- This tool enforces a result cap by default to prevent context bloating. If the cap is hit, the response will include a truncation warning instructing you to call the tool again with `bypassCap` set to `true` to retrieve the full result set.\n\n## Filters\n- `resourceTypes`: Required. Must include at least one resource type to filter results by. Resource types are in UpperCamelCase and plural. The list of exact resource type strings can be obtained by calling GetResourceTypesForDataset.\n- `keyword`: Search resources by keyword against resource names\n- `relatedTo`: Find resources related to specific resources (provide their resource ids)\n- `bypassCap`: Set to `true` only after instructed by a truncation warning and you are sure you will need the full set of resources. Defaults to `false`.\n- Multiple filters can be combined\n\n## Output\nA filtered JSON array of matching semantic resources. Each resource preserves its id, name, and type, but only includes the data fields relevant to your `resourcesPrompt`. Results are partial — if you need additional fields later, call the tool again with an updated `resourcesPrompt`.\nIf the dataset is not found or no resources match, the result will say so."};var UcSNk={Fe:UcDd.llg,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-documents"),description:['## Role\nFind documents by **semantic similarity** — meaning or topic — to a natural-language query, scoped to documents the current user can access. Uses vector (k-NN) search over document embeddings, so it matches conceptually related documents even when they don\'t share the query\'s exact words.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Return documents whose contents are semantically closest to the query, ranked most-similar first.\n- Each result includes the document\'s id and its title (when resolvable).\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use this tool for topic / meaning / conceptual questions: "Q3 marketing strategy", "onboarding flows", "data retention".\n- Phrase the query as the user\'s intent; the tool embeds the whole phrase rather than matching keywords.\n- Avoid meta **searchText** that includes phrases like "documents about" or "docs pertaining to" — choose **searchText** that relates to the desired content, not the context of the query or the medium.\n\n## When NOT to use\n- Exact keyword or title lookups ("the doc titled \'Roadmap\'", "docs containing \'invoice #4421\'") — use the keyword document search tool instead.\n- Recency or activity questions ("what did I edit last week", "docs I worked on with Priya") — use the Activity Search tool instead.\n\n## Limitations\n- Results are scoped to documents the current user already has access to.\n- It returns document ids and titles — not full document contents.\n- It cannot create, edit, share, rename, or delete documents.']};var UcTNk={Fe:UcDd.Kmc,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'Applies a single named property value to a single shape-like item.\n\n## When to Use\n- After calling ShapeDetails to retrieve the item\'s ShapeSchema.\n- When setting a value that the schema describes as supported (card fields like `title` and `status`, or advanced properties exposed to AI).\n- Call this tool once per property; to set multiple properties on the same item, issue multiple tool calls.\n\n## Input\n- `shapeId`: the ID of the item to mutate.\n- `propertyName`: the name of the property to set. Must match a name declared in the item\'s ShapeSchema.\n- `value`: the value to apply, encoded as a string.\n- `valueType`: tells the client how to coerce the string value — "string", "number", or "boolean".\n\n## Output\nA confirmation that the property was applied, or an error describing why it could not be.\n\n## Notes\n- This tool does not change geometry, position, or rotation — use *MoveBlock* or *ResizeBlock* for those.'};var UcUNk={Fe:UcDd.yL,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'## Role\nOpens the share dialog so the user can copy a link or invite collaborators by email.\n\n## When to use\n- The user asks to share the document, get a link, send it to someone, or invite people.\n- Examples: "share this", "copy a link to this diagram", "send this to my team", "invite Alex to edit".'};var UcVNk={Fe:UcDd.hsa,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nSorts, categorizes, or clusters objects on the canvas into named groups.\n\n## Capabilities\n\n- Takes a list of canvas objects, **makes a copy**, and sorts them into groups based on shared characteristics, relationships, or user-defined criteria\n- Can **identify patterns, similarities, or connections** between objects to create meaningful groupings\n- Does **not** move or modify the original objects — creates new copies organized into groups\n- Can **not** operate on diagrams, only standalone items\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n\n- **Always pass ItemIds** when the user has asked for specific items to be sorted\n  - e.g., if the user says "Sort the sticky notes based on priority", include the ItemIds of those sticky notes (identify them by reading the canvas)\n- If **no ItemIds** are provided, the tool attempts to sort the user\'s **selected items** — leave ItemIds blank if the user wants to sort the selection\n- If no ItemIds and no selection, the tool sorts **all canvas objects** — this should be rare, so try to provide ItemIds whenever possible\n\n## Important Warnings\n\n- If the user asks for **specific shapes** to be sorted, you **must** call FilterCanvas first to identify the ItemIds — failure to do so may result in sorting the wrong items\n- **Always read the canvas first**, unless the user just wants to summarize the selection',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-sorting-shapes")};var UcWNk={Fe:UcDd.j8e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nGenerates structured canvas content using the Standard Import format and places it directly on the canvas.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- Create a **new board layout** from a text description\n- Generate **structured content** like retrospectives, sprint planning boards, brainstorming sessions, etc.\n- Set up a **board template** based on their described workflow\n- Create **organized layouts** with sticky notes, containers, or grouped content\n\n## How It Works\n\n- Takes a detailed text prompt describing the desired content\n- Generates the corresponding **document structure** using the Standard Import format and places it on the canvas\n- The prompt should include **all relevant context** since the tool cannot see the chat history or existing canvas content",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-importing-diagram-data")};var UcXNk={Fe:UcDd.Smg,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,RU:i18n.get("ai-assistant-summarize-documents-loading-text"),description:'## Role\n\nSummarizes the contents of one or more documents the user can access, identified by document ID. The documents do not need to be open — the summary is produced from each document\'s stored content. When several documents are provided, they are combined into a single unified summary of the group.\n\n## When to use\n\nUse this tool when the user wants a summary, overview, or recap of one or more **specific documents** they have already located (for example, documents returned by the search tool). Pass the document IDs that were surfaced. To summarize several documents, pass them all in a single call — they will be combined into one unified summary rather than summarized separately.\n\n## Examples of user requests that indicate this tool should be used\n- "Summarize that document"\n- "Give me an overview of these docs"\n- "What are these documents about?" (after documents have been found)\n\n## When NOT to use\n- Do **not** use this tool to summarize the document the user is actively editing on the canvas; that is handled by a separate in-document summary flow.\n- Do **not** call this tool with a document ID you have not actually obtained from a prior tool result — only summarize documents that have been located.\n\n## Important notes\n- This tool supports Lucidchart and Lucidspark documents.'};var UcYNk={Fe:UcDd.t8e,lYb:!0,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-syncing-jira-to-dynamic-table"),description:["## Role\nUse this tool to import Jira issues onto an existing Lucid dynamic table and set up ongoing auto-sync between the table and Jira.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The JQL query should have been validated using the JiraSearch tool to confirm it returns the expected issues.\n- A dynamic table must already exist — use the CreateDynamicTable tool or the CanvasQuery tool to get a dynamic table.\n- The user must be authenticated to Jira.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Imports Jira issues matching a JQL query as cards and places them onto a specific dynamic table\n- Configures ongoing auto-sync so new Jira issues matching the query automatically appear on the table\n- Updates the existing sync config if one is already configured on the table (e.g., to change the JQL query)\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId of an existing dynamic table on the canvas\n- Use the same JQL query that was validated with JiraSearch\n- Call this AFTER CreateDynamicTable has created the table (or after you have obtained a dynamic table ID using CanvasQuery)\n- If a sync config already exists on the table, this tool updates the JQL and re-syncs\n\n## Limitations\n- Does not create dynamic tables — use CreateDynamicTable for that\n- Does not change table settings like pivots or capacity planning — use EditDynamicTableMetadata for that\n- Requires a valid Jira connection"]};var UcZNk={Fe:UcDd.u8e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,lYb:!0,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-syncing-jira-to-timeline"),description:["## Role\nUse this tool to import Jira issues onto an existing Lucid timeline and set up ongoing auto-sync between the timeline and Jira.\n\n## Prerequisites\n- The JQL query should have been validated using the JiraSearch tool to confirm it returns the expected issues.\n- A timeline must already exist — use the CreateLucidTimeline tool first.\n- The user must be authenticated to Jira.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Imports Jira issues matching a JQL query as cards and places them onto a specific timeline\n- Configures ongoing auto-sync so new Jira issues matching the query automatically appear on the timeline\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Use the generatorId returned by the CreateLucidTimeline tool\n- Use the same JQL query that was validated with JiraSearch\n- Call this AFTER CreateLucidTimeline has created the timeline\n\n## Limitations\n- Does not create timelines — use CreateLucidTimeline for that\n- Requires a valid Jira connection"]};var Uc_Nk={Fe:UcDd.mge,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"Add a new entry to the task list."};var Uc0Nk={Fe:UcDd.nge,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"Clear all entries from the task list."};var Uc1Nk={Fe:UcDd.jBd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"Mark a task list entry as completed. Purposely only supports marking off a single item as done at a time. This is because you should be doing tasks one at a time, and marking them off as you go. Marking off multiple tasks at once is a sign that you are not following your task list closely enough."};var Uc2Nk={Fe:UcDd.a9a,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nCreates a visual board — a structured canvas layout — from natural language descriptions. A board is a visual workspace organized into **labeled sections (frames)**, each containing content such as **sticky notes, tables, and swimlanes**. Boards are ideal for any activity that benefits from **visual organization, categorization, or structured thinking** — not just software/agile contexts.\n\n## When to use this tool\nUse this tool when the user wants to:\n- Create a new board layout from a text description\n- Generate structured content like retrospectives, sprint planning boards, brainstorming sessions, etc.\n- Create or fill in a **table** (e.g., itinerary, comparison matrix, schedule, tracker)\n- Create a **roadmap** (e.g., project milestones, release plan)\n- Prepare a template-like workspace that participants can fill in, e.g., set up a SWOT analysis\n- Set up a board template based on their described workflow\n- Organized, structured brainstorming with labeled sections (e.g., "brainstorm pros and cons")\n\n## When NOT to use this tool\n- Connected diagrams like flowcharts or ERDs — use Generate Diagram instead\n- A single shape or sticky note — use Add Block or Generate Ideas instead\n- A flat list of brainstormed ideas without board structure (e.g., "brainstorm names for my project") — use Generate Ideas instead\n\n## After using this tool\nSummarize what was created (board title, frame names, structure). Do NOT restate the user\'s request.\n\n## How it works\nThe tool analyzes the user\'s request to determine what type of board they want to create, then generates the appropriate board structure and content.',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-board")};var Uc3Nk={Fe:UcDd.S4c,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,description:"## Role\n\nGives you a place to think out loud for document analysis, task planning, and complex reasoning. This tool returns no output — the value is in organizing your thoughts before acting.\n\n## Usage\n\nAlways include ThinkAloud **alongside** your first batch of action tools in the same wave.\n\n## Hard Rule\n\nYou must **NEVER** respond with a wave that consists only of one or more ThinkAloud tool calls.  Your responses should ALWAYS have more tools in here as well; thinking aloud does not get you closer to completing the user's task.\n\n## Planning Guidance\n\nWhen planning, explicitly identify:\n- Which operations are **independent** and can be batched in the current wave\n- Which operations have **data dependencies** (need IDs or state from current-wave tools) and must wait for the next wave"};var Uc4Nk={Fe:UcDd.u9f,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'Converts the current diagram or selected items into Mermaid code.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Reads the diagram content and generates valid Mermaid syntax\n- Auto-detects the best mermaid diagram type (flowchart, classDiagram, erDiagram, sequenceDiagram, stateDiagram, mindmap, etc.)\n- Preserves labels, text content, and relationships from the diagram\n- Can export specific items by ID or the full page\n\n## When to use\n- When the user asks to export, convert, or generate Mermaid code from their diagram\n- When the user wants a text representation of their diagram in Mermaid format\n- When the user mentions "mermaid" in the context of exporting or converting\n\n## When NOT to use\n- When the user wants to import Mermaid code into a diagram (use StandardImport or GenerateDiagram instead)\n- When the user wants a summary or description of their diagram (use Summarize instead)\n\n## Selection behavior\n- If items are selected on the canvas, export those items without asking — do NOT prompt the user to confirm scope\n- If nothing is selected, attempt to export the current page; if that\'s not possible, ask which diagram to export\n\n## Tool Output\n- After this tool completes, the tool result will contain the generated Mermaid code.\n- You MUST use MessageUser to display the Mermaid code to the user exactly as it appears in the tool result. Do not modify, summarize, or omit any part of the code.\n- Include a brief message (e.g. "Here\'s the exported Mermaid code:") before the code block.',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-mermaid")};var Uc5Nk={Fe:UcDd.O$f,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\nGenerates a diagram within the agent\'s semantic domain from a prompt using the domain\'s shape library, then matches the resulting shapes to the semantic resources you referenced so they can be created as **data-backed shapes** linked to live data.\n\n## How It Works\n- You provide a natural-language prompt describing the desired architecture and the IDs of the semantic resources that informed it (`usedResourceIds`).\n- The tool generates the diagram, then a matching step links each generated shape to a corresponding resource when one exists. Shapes with no matching resource remain regular (non-data-backed) shapes.\n\n## When to Use\n- When the user wants to create a diagram that incorporates live data from semantic datasets in the document.\n- Only after querying the semantic data (using *GetResourceTypesForDataset*, *GetResourceSchemasForDataset*, *QuerySemanticResources*, etc.) to understand what resources are available.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Before using query tools to understand the available data — always gather data context first.\n- For general diagrams with no data backing — use *GenerateDiagram* instead.\n- For non-domain diagrams.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Do NOT include semantic framework terminology ("semantic data", "datasets", "semantic resources") in the prompt — the tool handles data-backing internally.\n- All shapes must use the domain\'s shape library only.',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-diagram")};var Uc6Nk={Fe:UcDd.l3e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\nGenerates a diagram within the agent\'s semantic domain from a prompt using the domain\'s shape library, then matches the resulting shapes to the semantic resources you referenced so they can be created as **data-backed shapes** linked to live data. Can also regenerate an existing diagram in place while keeping its shapes data-backed.\n\n## How It Works\n- You provide a natural-language prompt describing the desired architecture and the IDs of the semantic resources that informed it (`usedResourceIds`).\n- The tool generates the diagram, then a matching step links each generated shape to a corresponding resource when one exists. Shapes with no matching resource remain regular (non-data-backed) shapes.\n- To change a diagram you already created, pass its container ID as `diagramIdToReplace`. The diagram is rebuilt from your prompt and the matching step runs again, so the rebuilt shapes stay data-backed.\n\n## When to Use\n- When the user wants to create a diagram that incorporates live data from semantic datasets in the document.\n- For **any** change to a diagram this tool produced — re-layout, restyling, or changing which resources it shows. Pass `diagramIdToReplace` so the rebuilt diagram keeps its data-backing.\n- Only after querying the semantic data (using *GetResourceTypesForDataset*, *GetResourceSchemasForDataset*, *QuerySemanticResources*, etc.) to understand what resources are available.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- Before using query tools to understand the available data — always gather data context first.\n- For non-domain diagrams.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Do NOT include semantic framework terminology ("semantic data", "datasets", "semantic resources") in the prompt — the tool handles data-backing internally.\n- All shapes must use the domain\'s shape library only.\n- When regenerating (`diagramIdToReplace` set), describe the full desired end state in the prompt and re-supply the relevant `datasetIds`/`usedResourceIds` — the diagram is rebuilt from scratch.',
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-generating-diagram")};var Uc7Nk={Fe:UcDd.Uyd,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-get-document-history-loading-text"),qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"Returns the most recent document actions in chronological order.\n\nEach action has an `Action` field indicating its type and some additional fields depending on the type of the action.\n\nWhen to use:\n- To understand what the user was recently working on before their current request\n- To detect changes made outside your own tool calls (e.g. manual user edits between turns)\n- To verify whether a previous operation produced the expected result"};var Uc8Nk={Fe:UcDd.msa,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!0,description:['## Role\nUse this tool to undo canvas actions when the user asks to go back, undo, revert, or ctrl+z their changes.\nThe tool will automatically display a confirmation dialog to the user — you do not need to ask for confirmation first.\n\n## When to Use\n- User says "undo", "go back", "revert", "ctrl+z", "undo that", "take that back", or similar\n- User expresses dissatisfaction with recent AI-made changes and wants them reversed\n- User asks to undo multiple steps (e.g. "undo the last 3 changes") — set Steps accordingly\n\n## Parameters\n- **Steps** (optional): Number of undo steps to revert. Omit or set to 1 for a single undo. Set to the number the user specifies for multi-step requests.\n\n## Limitations\n- Each step undoes one undo batch (one logical change)\n- If there is nothing to undo, the tool will inform the user']};var Uc9Nk={Fe:UcDd.V8e,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:'## Role\n\nUpdate one or more existing AI suggestions in place. Each entry replaces the suggestion\'s **type**,\n**title**, and **description** while preserving its status (Open) and originating agent. Use this\nto refine an existing suggestion rather than dismissing it and creating a new one.\n\n## When to Use\n- A **contextNeeded** suggestion has been answered — update it in place to type \'recommendation\'\n  with a proposed change as the new title/description. Propose a refinement even when the\n  answer reads as informational (e.g. tightening a label to include the new detail, adding a\n  note, splitting an item); the user can confirm or decline. If the answer truly maps\n  to no useful change, only then can you skip Update and just resolve the suggestion via\n  *ResolveAiSuggestions*.\n  - *Example:* contextNeeded "What does this box represent?" → user answers "it\'s the step where\n    the request gets approved" → update to a recommendation titled "Relabel this box to \'Approve\n    request\'" with the rationale in the description.\n- The user has reshaped a recommendation (e.g. "but do it for the rejection branch instead") and the\n  existing suggestion\'s title/description need to reflect the new direction.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- To dismiss or apply a suggestion — use *ResolveAiSuggestions* instead.\n- To create a new suggestion on an item that has no active one — use *CreateAiSuggestions*.\n- For item IDs not associated with an Open suggestion in the *ReadAiSuggestions* results. Those entries\n  are skipped.\n\n## How It Works\n- Provide an **updates** list, each entry with **itemId**, the new **suggestionType**, **title**,\n  and **description**.\n- Bundle every refinement into a single tool call rather than making multiple calls.\n- **Always call *ReadAiSuggestions* first**, then take **itemId** values from its results; do not invent IDs.\n- Entries referencing items not associated with an Open suggestion are skipped.'};var Uc$Nk={Fe:UcDd.Cog,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-searching-users"),description:["## Role\nResolve a person's name or email to candidate numeric user IDs within the current account, so other tools can filter by that person.\n\n## Capabilities\n- Run a fuzzy search over the account's users by name or email and return candidate matches, each with a numeric user ID, full name, and email.\n\n## Usage Guidelines\n- Call this **first** whenever the user references another person by name and you need their user ID.\n- The search may return more than one candidate. If the match is ambiguous, use the returned names / emails to disambiguate, or ask the user which person they meant before relying on an ID.\n\n## Limitations\n- Only finds users within the current account.\n- Returns identity information, not documents.\n- Never guess or invent user IDs. If no candidate matches, say so plainly."]};var UcaOk={Fe:UcDd.i5c,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nCreates a container around existing blocks on the canvas. Can also wrap one or more generators in a frame.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- When blocks need to be grouped into a container\n- Use assisted layout (default) when blocks should be arranged in a grid\n- Use non-assisted layout when blocks should keep their current positions\n- **To frame one or more generators:** pass that generator ids item IDs. The frame is created with a default title — give it a label by calling `EditTextArea` on the returned frame ID afterward.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Only block IDs or generator IDs are valid; line IDs and nonexistent IDs are skipped with error messages\n- When using assisted layout, blocks **cannot already be** in an assisted layout container\n- Generator framing only applies when evert item ID that is passed is a generator; mixing a generator with other IDs falls back to block wrapping"};var UcbOk={[Uc0pb.mf]:"ss_presetShapeStyle1",[Uc0pb.Ars]:"ss_presetShapeStyle2",[Uc0pb.dDs]:"ss_presetShapeStyle3",[Uc0pb.kOh]:"ss_presetShapeStyle4",[Uc0pb.Highlight]:"ss_presetShapeStyle5",[Uc0pb.Taa]:"ss_presetShapeStyle6",[Uc0pb.Error]:"ss_presetShapeStyle7"};var UccOk,UcdOk=UccOk=class{constructor(a){this.jX=a.jX;this.rap=a.rap;this.dF=a.dF;this.ump=a.ump;this.dkq=a.dkq;this.ekq=a.ekq}toJSON(){return UccOk.Na(this)}};UcdOk=UccOk=__decorate([Ucn({jX:["FeatureName",Uco],dkq:["Stale3MonthDate",Ucm(Uc4c)],ekq:["Stale6MonthDate",Ucm(Uc4c)],ump:["LongTermIgnoreDate",Ucm(Uc4c)],rap:["IsPermanentlyIgnored",Uc7c],dF:["Team",Uco]})],UcdOk);var UceOk,UcfOk=UceOk=class{constructor(a){this.qtc=a.qtc;this.key=a.key;this.start=a.start}toJSON(){return UceOk.Na(this)}},UcgOk=UcfOk=UceOk=__decorate([Ucn({qtc:["FeatureId",Uco],start:["Start",Uc3c],key:["Key",Uco]})],UcfOk);var UchOk,UciOk=UchOk=class{constructor(a){this.created=a.created;this.YHo=a.YHo;this.UPa=a.UPa;this.jIo=a.jIo;this.updated=a.updated}toJSON(){return UchOk.Na(this)}};UciOk=UchOk=__decorate([Ucn({UPa:["FilterId",Uco],jIo:["FilterTitle",Uco],YHo:["FilterEntry",Uco],created:["Created",Uc4c],updated:["Updated",Uc4c]})],UciOk);var UcjOk,UckOk=UcjOk=class{constructor(a){this.active=a.active;this.effectiveDate=a.effectiveDate;this.expirationDate=a.expirationDate;this.link=a.link;this.primary=a.primary;this.DNh=a.DNh;this.isForEncryption=a.isForEncryption;this.privateKey=a.privateKey}toJSON(){return UcjOk.Na(this)}},UclOk=UckOk=UcjOk=__decorate([Ucn({link:["Link",Uco],privateKey:["PrivateKey",Ucm(Uco)],DNh:["X509cert",Uco],effectiveDate:["EffectiveDate",Uc4c],expirationDate:["ExpirationDate",Uc4c],active:["Active",Uc7c],primary:["Primary",
