Uc7Ok=Uc6Ok=__decorate([Ucn({Yn:["blueprintId",Uco],method:["method",UcbDb],Tld:["moduleIds",Uc2c(Uco)],udb:["recipientType",UcnJk],Cra:["teamIds",Uc2c(Ucbd)],userId:["userId",Ucbd],$fh:["numTeamsSharedWith",Ucm(Ucbd)],qzb:["teamTagId",Ucm(Uco)],name:["name",UcPe("sharedBlueprint")]})],Uc7Ok);var Uc8Ok,Uc9Ok=Uc8Ok=class{constructor(a){this.name="openedTemplatePicker";this.userId=a.userId;this.pe=a.pe;this.INl=a.INl;this.templateId=a.templateId}toJSON(){return Uc8Ok.Na(this)}};Uc9Ok.Jc="openedTemplatePicker";Uc9Ok=Uc8Ok=__decorate([Ucn({userId:["userId",Ucbd],pe:["entryPoint",Ucm(UcaEb)],INl:["landingPage",Ucm(UcwJk)],templateId:["templateId",Ucm(Ucbd)],name:["name",UcPe("openedTemplatePicker")]})],Uc9Ok);var Uc$Ok,UcaPk=Uc$Ok=class{constructor(a){this.name="toggleHeaderField";this.dataType=a.dataType;this.documentId=a.documentId;this.XIe=a.XIe;this.state=a.state;this.userId=a.userId}toJSON(){return Uc$Ok.Na(this)}};UcaPk.Jc="toggleHeaderField";UcaPk=Uc$Ok=__decorate([Ucn({userId:["userId",Ucbd],documentId:["documentId",Uco],dataType:["dataType",UccIk],state:["state",UcgIk],XIe:["numSelectedShapes",Ucbd],name:["name",UcPe("toggleHeaderField")]})],UcaPk);var UcbPk,UccPk=UcbPk=class{constructor(a){this.name="updatedUserSetting";this.location=a.location;this.XBc=a.XBc;this.fRe=a.fRe;this.userId=a.userId}toJSON(){return UcbPk.Na(this)}};UccPk.Jc="updatedUserSetting";UccPk=UcbPk=__decorate([Ucn({location:["location",UcBJk],XBc:["settingName",UcFJk],fRe:["settingValue",Uco],userId:["userId",Ucbd],name:["name",UcPe("updatedUserSetting")]})],UccPk);var UcdPk,UcePk=UcdPk=class{constructor(a){this.name="viewedAttachedFile";this.QR=a.QR;this.method=a.method;this.permissions=a.permissions;this.userId=a.userId}toJSON(){return UcdPk.Na(this)}};UcePk.Jc="viewedAttachedFile";UcePk=UcdPk=__decorate([Ucn({method:["method",UcLJk],permissions:["permissions",UcRBb],QR:["fileId",Uco],userId:["userId",Ucbd],name:["name",UcPe("viewedAttachedFile")]})],UcePk);var UcfPk,UcgPk=UcfPk=class{constructor(a){this.values=a.values;this.created=a.created;this.ZF=a.ZF;this.start=a.start}toJSON(){return UcfPk.Na(this)}},UchPk=UcgPk=UcfPk=__decorate([Ucn({start:["Start",Ucm(Uc3c)],values:["Values",Ucyd(Uco,Uco)],created:["Created",Ucm(Uc3c)],ZF:["Creator",Ucm(Uco)]})],UcgPk);var UciPk,UcjPk=UciPk=class{constructor(a){this.id=a.id;this.selection=a.selection;this.tke=a.tke;this.Ymo=a.Ymo}toJSON(){return UciPk.Na(this)}},UckPk=UcjPk=UciPk=__decorate([Ucn({id:["Id",Uco],selection:["Selection",UchKk],Ymo:["DataKeys",Ucm(Uc2c(Uco))],tke:["AssignmentAlgorithm",Ucm(UcYRb)]})],UcjPk);var UclPk,UcmPk=UclPk=class{constructor(a){this.$nc=a.$nc;this.MPn=a.MPn;this.NPn=a.NPn;this.I0n=a.I0n;this.K0n=a.K0n;this.d6n=a.d6n;this.captchaToken=a.captchaToken;this.yGg=a.yGg;this.Lpf=a.Lpf;this.firstName=a.firstName;this.g0g=a.g0g;this.lastName=a.lastName;this.level=a.level;this.YZd=a.YZd;this.bSp=a.bSp;this.cSp=a.cSp;this.slug=a.slug;this.Fkq=a.Fkq;this.T_c=a.T_c;this.trial=a.trial;this.gXe=a.gXe;this.HBq=a.HBq;this.VBq=a.VBq}toJSON(){return UclPk.Na(this)}},UcnPk=UcmPk=UclPk=__decorate([Ucn({level:["level",
Ucm(Uco)],slug:["slug",Ucm(Uco)],NPn:["additionalStorage",Ucm(Ucad)],MPn:["additionalLicenses",Ucm(Ucad)],$nc:["absoluteLicenses",Ucm(Ucad)],yGg:["couponCode",Ucm(Uco)],bSp:["billingToken",Ucm(Uco)],cSp:["billingTokenType",Ucm(UciKk)],captchaToken:["invisibleCaptchaToken",Ucm(Uco)],K0n:["billingInfo.postalCode",Ucm(Uco)],I0n:["billingInfo.countryCode",Ucm(Uco)],HBq:["useBillingInfoOnFile",Ucm(Uc7c)],d6n:["canUseCache",Ucm(Uc7c)],trial:["trial",Ucm(Uc7c)],gXe:["trialLength",Ucm(Ucad)],VBq:["useDirectDebit",
Ucm(Uc7c)],firstName:["firstName",Ucm(Uco)],lastName:["lastName",Ucm(Uco)],Lpf:["lucidscale-explorer",Ucm(Ucad)],Fkq:["startSubscriptionAfterTrial",Ucm(Uc7c)],YZd:["purchaseFlow",Ucm(UcsJk)],T_c:["threeDSecureResultToken",Ucm(Uco)],g0g:["HasAgreedToAutoRenewalDisclosure",Ucm(Uc7c)]})],UcmPk);var UcoPk={Fe:UcDd.tNa,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,Nvb:!0,description:['## Role\n\nDisplay structured clarifying questions when user requests are ambiguous or lack sufficient detail. Collect specific information needed to proceed with a task. Present questions in a clear, user-friendly form format.\n\n## When to Use:\n- USE TO ask questions about context you could never figure out from other tool calls.\n> **EXAMPLE** - User says "I need help with diagraming my project, but I\'m not sure where to start.  Can you help me?"\n- 1. Context is not possible to gather from other tool calls.  Only the user can provide the context you need.\n- 2. So, Immediately use this tool to ask clarifying questions.\n\n## When NOT to Use:\n- DO NOT USE before using other tools that could provide the information you need.\n> **EXAMPLE** -  User says "I\'m confused, can you walk me through this diagram?"\n> **EXAMPLE** -  User says "What improvements should I make to this workflow?"\n- 1. Use a tool to gather context and determine what the user is referring to.\n- 2. If it is still unclear what the user is talking about, *then* use this tool to ask a clarifying question.\n\n## How It Works\n\n- You provide the **contextMessage** and **questionForm**\n- The tool displays them to the user as an interactive form\n- After the user answers, you receive their responses and can proceed\n- If the user responds with **"Skip clarification questions"**, proceed immediately without re-asking — use your best judgment and placeholders for any missing details\n\n## Question Guidelines\n\n- Keep questions **clear, concise, and focused**\n- **Default to multi-select** for any question with predefined options. Most questions accept more than one answer, and the user should be free to pick multiple.\n  - Use **single-select** only when the options are strictly mutually exclusive by nature: binary either/or, ordering, or strict enumerations where exactly one value can apply.\n  - *Never* create "Both", "All of the above", or "X and Y" as a single option — that is a sign you should be using multi-select instead.\n- Provide helpful option labels that are easy to understand\n- Include a **context message** to explain why you\'re asking these questions\n- Keep the number of questions minimal (**2-3 questions max**)\n- Make sure each question is **necessary** to proceed\n- Do not ask for information you already have from context',
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."]};var UcpPk={Fe:UcDd.OJ,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nHelp users apply, modify, or remove conditional formatting rules on the canvas. You are **not** able to delete any rules.\n\n## Capabilities\n- The system can format shapes based on almost any criteria that can be determined from looking at the canvas.\n- The system can apply the following visual effects: **background color**, **border color**, **text color**, or a predefined **shape style** or **icon**.\n- If the user's request falls outside these capabilities, the rule **cannot** be created.\n- After you've clarified requirements you should submit requests to this tool even if you're not sure it can be accomplished.\n- If the tool can't complete the request, it will return an error message explaining why - which you may be able to use to try again or explain to the user.\n\n### Picking IsComplex\n\nSet IsComplex correctly on the first call — the simple path rejects multi-condition rules and forces a wasted retry.\n\nPass **IsComplex=true** when the rule involves any of:\n- More than one condition (e.g. \"sticky notes that contain 'urgent'\" has the conditions \"is a sticky note\" and \"contains the text 'urgent'\")\n- AND/OR/NOT logic combining conditions\n- A formula, calculation, or relative comparison between shapes\n\nPass **IsComplex=false** for a rule built on a single straightforward criterion (text content, shape type, a single shape-data field, connection count, or container membership).\n\nEven with IsComplex=true the tool can't analyze semantic content — capability limits still apply.\n\n## Interaction Guidelines\n\n- Before making changes, **always clarify** which shapes the user wants to edit — ask the user to specify verbally; if unclear, prompt them to manually select the shapes.\n- If the request is vague, **ask for more context** about the desired changes.\n- **Always explain** what conditional formatting changes will be applied.\n- Maintain a **friendly, collaborative, and action-oriented** tone.\n- Provide a **short (2-5 word) descriptive title** that will be used as the title of the generated or updated rule.\n- If the user requests a specific title, you **must** include that rule name so the tool will use it.\n\n## Editing Existing Rules\n\n- In order to edit a rule, you must include the rule ID to be edited in the RuleIdToEdit field.\n- You can get the rule ID to edit from the list of already-created rules in conversation history, or from the user message directly.\n- Users are not aware of rule IDs or the existence of rule IDs — ask them to **select from the list** of already-created rules in conversation history by name. Never ask the user for a rule ID directly.\n- If the user is editing an existing rule, forward their request to the tool - you cannot see the details of the existing rule, but the subagent can. The user does not need to describe the entire condition and effect when editing.\n- If the user is trying to edit a **deleted rule**, inform them.\n\n## General Guidelines\n\n- If the user requests to **delete** a rule, inform them that you are unable to do so.\n- If the request combines **multiple effects** with **different conditions** (e.g., \"make shapes with 'High' red and shapes with 'Low' green\"), break these into **separate tool calls**, each with its own title, condition, and effect.\n- Rules apply deterministically and globally (based on values such as shape text, shape data, shape type, connections to other shapes, container membership, and more).\n- If the user's request implies multiple rules, you MUST make multiple tool calls. One tool call CANNOT and MUST NOT carry more than one rule.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-updating-rules")};var UcqPk={Fe:UcDd.ayd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nHelp the user add a **new** conditional formatting rule to the canvas. You are **not** able to delete or modify existing rules through this tool.\n\n## Capabilities\n- The system can format shapes based on almost any criteria that can be determined from looking at the canvas.\n- The system can apply the following visual effects: **background color**, **border color**, **text color**, or a predefined **shape style** or **icon**.\n- If the user's request falls outside these capabilities, the rule **cannot** be created.\n- After you've clarified requirements you should submit requests to this tool even if you're not sure it can be accomplished.\n- If the tool can't complete the request, it will return an error message explaining why - which you may be able to use to try again or explain to the user.\n\n### Picking IsComplex\n\nSet IsComplex correctly on the first call — the simple path rejects multi-condition rules and forces a wasted retry.\n\nPass **IsComplex=true** when the rule involves any of:\n- More than one condition (e.g. \"sticky notes that contain 'urgent'\" has the conditions \"is a sticky note\" and \"contains the text 'urgent'\")\n- AND/OR/NOT logic combining conditions\n- A formula, calculation, or relative comparison between shapes\n\nPass **IsComplex=false** for a rule built on a single straightforward criterion (text content, shape type, a single shape-data field, connection count, or container membership).\n\nOnly flip your initial IsComplex=false decision after the first call fails because the request turned out to be more complex than it looked.\n\n## Interaction Guidelines\n\n- Before making changes, **always clarify** which shapes the user wants to format — if unclear, prompt them to manually select the shapes or describe them in their message.\n- If the request is vague, **ask for more context** about the desired condition and effect.\n- **Always explain** what conditional formatting rule will be created.\n- Provide a **short (2-5 word) descriptive title** that will be used as the title of the generated or updated rule.\n- If the user requests a specific title, you **must** include that rule name so the tool will use it.\n\n## General Guidelines\n\n- If the user requests to **delete** a rule, inform them that you are unable to do so.\n- If the request combines **multiple effects** with **different conditions** (e.g., \"make shapes with 'High' red and shapes with 'Low' green\"), break these into **separate tool calls**, each with its own title, condition, and effect.\n- Rules apply deterministically and globally (based on values such as shape text, shape data, shape type, connections to other shapes, container membership, and more).\n- If the user's request implies multiple rules, you MUST make multiple tool calls. One tool call CANNOT and MUST NOT carry more than one rule.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-updating-rules")};var UcrPk={Fe:UcDd.Cyd,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,description:"## Role\n\nModify an **existing** conditional formatting rule on the canvas. You are **not** able to delete rules.\n\n## Identifying the rule\n\n- Pass the rule's ID in the **RuleId** field. Get this from the list of already-created rules in conversation history.\n- Users are not aware of rule IDs — ask them to **select from the list** of already-created rules by name. Never ask the user for a rule ID directly.\n- If the user is trying to edit a **deleted rule**, inform them that the rule no longer exists.\n\n## Interaction Guidelines\n\n- You **do not** see the current details of the rule — forward the user's requested change verbatim and let the tool reconcile against the existing rule. The user does not need to re-describe the full rule when editing.\n- If the user requests a new title, include it in the command text so the tool can update the rule name.\n\n### Picking IsComplex\n\nSet IsComplex correctly on the first call — the simple path rejects multi-condition rules and forces a wasted retry.\n\nPass **IsComplex=true** when the rule involves any of:\n- More than one condition (e.g. \"sticky notes that contain 'urgent'\" has the conditions \"is a sticky note\" and \"contains the text 'urgent'\")\n- AND/OR/NOT logic combining conditions\n- A formula, calculation, or relative comparison between shapes\n\nPass **IsComplex=false** for a rule built on a single straightforward criterion (text content, shape type, a single shape-data field, connection count, or container membership).\n\nFor edits specifically, \"more than one condition\" applies when the edit itself introduces new condition logic — adding a second condition, swapping in AND/OR/NOT, etc. The tool auto-promotes when the existing rule is already complex, but don't rely on that for new complexity introduced by *the edit itself*. Pass IsComplex=false for simple property edits (changing the effect, renaming, swapping a single condition value).\n\n## General Guidelines\n\n- If the user requests to **delete** a rule, inform them that you are unable to do so.\n- If the request combines **multiple effects** with **different conditions** (e.g., \"make shapes with 'High' red and shapes with 'Low' green\"), break these into **separate tool calls**, each with its own title, condition, and effect.\n- Rules apply deterministically and globally (based on values such as shape text, shape data, shape type, connections to other shapes, container membership, and more).\n- If the user's request implies multiple rules, you MUST make multiple tool calls. One tool call CANNOT and MUST NOT carry more than one rule.",
RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-updating-rules")};var UcsPk={Fe:UcDd.wce,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.wf,Nvb:!0,description:['## Role\n\nPresents up to 4 candidate templates from the template library for the user to choose from. The user selects one and it is inserted into the document. This tool never imports a template on its own — it always asks the user to pick.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- The user asks for you to use a template\n- The user wants to bootstrap a document from a template (e.g. "start with a template about agile", "import an org chart template").\n- The user is in the middle of choosing a template and is now clarifying what kind they want (e.g. you previously asked "what kind of template?" and they replied with a topic, domain, or activity such as "for sprint planning", "a retrospective one", "something for SWOT"). In this case, call ImportTemplate immediately with their clarification as the search term.\n\n## Priority Over Agent Switching\n\nThis tool **takes priority over `SwitchAgent` routing rules** whenever the user has already expressed intent to use a template. If the user originally asked for a template and is now clarifying which one — even if the clarification mentions a topic that would normally route to another agent (e.g. "sprint board", "retrospective", "SWOT") — you MUST call ImportTemplate and MUST NOT call SwitchAgent. The user\'s stated intent to use a template wins; do not redirect them to board generation, diagram generation, or any other agent.\n\n## When NOT to Use\n\n- The user has asked you to generate a custom diagram from scratch — use GenerateDiagram.\n- The user is asking a question about an existing template already on the canvas.\n\n## Behavior\n\n- The tool shows the user up to 4 matching templates as a picker in the chat.\n- If the user ignores the picker, nothing is imported.\n- If no templates match the request, the tool fails and you should tell the user no templates were found.',
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."],RU:i18n.get("ai-tool-loading-importing-template-v2")};var UctPk={Fe:UcDd.UDa,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.yd,Nvb:!0,description:["## Role\n\nSend a message to the user — such as answering a question, providing a summary, or asking a clarifying question.\n\n**IMPORTANT:** When used to signal task completion, this **must be the *only* tool call in that round**.\n\n## Message Guidelines\n\n### Personality and Tone\n\n- **Friendly, collaborative, and action-oriented**\n- Focus on **clear, concise** communication\n\n### Clarifying Questions\n\n- If a user request is **vague or lacks sufficient detail**, ask clarifying questions before taking action\n- Do not select tools to run if a request could potentially be fulfilled by **multiple different tools** — ask for clarification first\n\n### Honesty About Limitations\n\n- Be **transparent** about what the assistant and tools can and cannot do, without excessive apologies\n\n### Refusal Policy\n\n- **Politely refuse** unsupported requests without lengthy apologies\n- Suggest **relevant alternatives** if appropriate\n\n## Technical Usage\n\n- Use the current date placeholder as `{{currentDate}}` when referencing today's date\n\n## Exclusion Rules\n\n- Do not include unnecessary **filler, greetings, or redundancy**\n- Remove any **internal metadata** (diagram IDs, item IDs, coordinates, technical identifiers, etc.)\n- *Never* provide **links or URLs** directly, whether in markdown format or not\n- Do not mention **tool internals**, schemas, or post-processing\n\n## Suggested Actions\n\n- You may optionally include **1-3 suggested follow-up actions** as clickable buttons via the *SuggestedActions* parameter",
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."]};var UcuPk={Fe:UcDd.FHc,qj:!1,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:"# Lucid Extension API — run_script Tool\n\n## What this tool does\n\nExecutes JavaScript code you provide against the Lucid document. Your code runs as an async function body. The return value (which must be JSON-serializable) is sent back to you, along with anything you logged via `console`. There is a hard 30-second timeout; only one script may run at a time. If your code throws, the error message is returned to you, but newly created items are NOT automatically rolled back.\n\n## Sandbox globals\n\nThree globals are injected: `client` (the `EditorClient`), `console`, and `sdk` (the entire `lucid-extension-sdk` module). Nothing else is in scope — there is no pre-defined `viewport` or `page`. Almost every script begins by deriving them:\n\n```js\nconst viewport = new sdk.Viewport(client);\nconst page = viewport.getCurrentPage();\n```\n\nExamples in canvas scripting skills assume you have run those two lines first. Any helper functions provided by skills are NOT pre-defined — paste the implementations you need into your script.\n\n## Persistence between calls\n\nEach call is a fresh sandbox — nothing survives between calls. `return` any IDs or values you need in later scripts; do not return proxy objects (blocks, lines, pages) as they are invalid outside the call that created them.\n\n## Acting on the user's selection\n\nWhen the request targets \"this\", \"the selected item\", or the current selection, edit the exact IDs from the `<current-user-direct-selection>` context in the user's message — that is what they had selected when they sent the request. Do **not** call `viewport.getSelectedItems()` to decide what to edit: it reads the live selection at the moment the script runs, which may have changed since the message was sent, so editing it can mutate the wrong item.\n\n```js\n// IDs come from <current-user-direct-selection> in the message context.\nconst selectedLineIds = ['8.a_m03rzofe'];\nfor (const id of selectedLineIds) {\n  const line = page.allLines.get(id);\n  if (line) line.textAreas.set('t0', 'next');\n}\n```\n\nOnly fall back to `viewport.getSelectedItems()` when no selection context was provided. Using `getSelectedItems()`/`setSelectedItems()` to read the selection non-destructively or to change it is fine.\n\n## Common SDK command errors\n\n### `Invalid parameters to command gp`\n\nUsually means a GetProperty call got a proxy where it expected an ID, or an ID where it expected a proxy.\n- Canvas-object APIs take proxies: line endpoint `connection`, `viewport.setSelectedItems(...)`, `viewport.focusCameraOnItems(...)`.\n- Lookup APIs take string IDs: `page.allBlocks.get(id)`, `page.allLines.get(id)`, `client.getBlockProxy(id)`.\n- `viewport.getSelectedItems()` returns proxies; use `item` for proxy APIs and `item.id` for lookups.\n\n```js\nconst selectedItem = viewport.getSelectedItems()[0]; // proxy\nconst target = page.allBlocks.get('target-block-id'); // ID lookup\n\npage.addLine({\n  endpoint1: { connection: selectedItem, linkX: 1, linkY: 0.5 },\n  endpoint2: { connection: target, linkX: 0, linkY: 0.5 },\n});\n\n// Wrong: lookup helper expects a string ID.\npage.allBlocks.get(selectedItem);\n```\n\n - Not all visible or searchable shape content lives in `block.textAreas.get('Text')`. Some shapes use named text areas, shape-specific properties, generated fields, or linked data. If `Text` is empty or does not match what is visible, use `shape_details` or Canvas Exploration before assuming the shape has no text.\n"};var UcvPk={Fe:UcDd.x6e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:'This tool executes a SPARQL SELECT query against a semantic dataset to retrieve matching resources.\nIt is a more powerful and efficient alternative to QuerySemanticResources, allowing querying by resource relationships (including containment) and filtering to specific fields in the resource schemas.\nHowever, it requires an exact understanding of the dataset\'s schema and SPARQL syntax to use effectively.\n\n## When to Use\n- To query resources based on specific fields in the schema e.g. "find all Persons with age 30"\n- To query resources based on relationships (including containment) e.g. "find all Persons in Department \'Engineering\'"\n\n## When NOT to Use\n- The current SPARQL engine can only make queries based on resource types, relationships, and named fields in the resources\' schemas. If the field is not explicitly defined in the resource schema, it cannot be queried with SPARQL.\n- You want to query a field and you don\'t have the schemas yet (use GetResourceSchemasForDataset first)\n- You want to query based on relationships and you don\'t have the relation definitions yet (use GetSemanticRelationDefinitions first)\n\n## When a query returns no results\nAn empty result almost never means the data is absent — it usually means the query was malformed, or a relationship was traversed in the wrong direction. Do NOT conclude the data is missing, and do NOT tell the user the resources lack the requested fields, links, or tags based on an empty result. Recover systematically:\n1. **Check relationship direction first.** A reversed subject/object is the most common cause of an empty traversal — verify your pattern follows the `from`/`to` order from GetSemanticRelationDefinitions (see Query Guidelines below).\n2. **Isolate the failing condition.** Drop one condition at a time and re-run — e.g. test the type/property filter without the relationship, then the relationship without the filter — to find which part returns nothing. Do NOT blindly guess new field names.\n3. **Fall back for the join.** If a relationship traversal still returns nothing after one corrected retry, STOP using SPARQL for that join: query the parent/anchor resource IDs, then call QuerySemanticResources with those IDs in the `relatedTo` parameter. For a property filter that won\'t resolve, fall back to QuerySemanticResources with equivalent filters.\n4. Only after these steps fail should you treat a field as genuinely unavailable — and describe it to the user as a retrieval limitation, not as the data being absent.\n\n## Query Guidelines\n- The SPARQL query should use urn:lucid:relationship as the relationship namespace prefix.\n  - The relationship predicate MUST match an exact string from GetSemanticRelationDefinitions.\n  - **Relationships are directional.** GetSemanticRelationDefinitions returns `{from, type, to}`. Your pattern MUST put the `from` type as the subject and the `to` type as the object: `?from <urn:lucid:relationship:type> ?to`. Example: if Accounts relate to VPCs via DescendantRef (from: Accounts, to: VPCs), write `?account <urn:lucid:relationship:DescendantRef> ?vpc` — NEVER the reverse. Reversing subject and object is the single most common cause of an empty result.\n- The SPARQL query should use urn:lucid:resource as the resource type namespace prefix.\n  - The type predicate MUST match an exact string from GetResourceTypesForDataset.\n- The SPARQL query should use urn:lucid:data as the data namespace prefix for querying based on fields in the resource schemas.\n  - The field predicate MUST match an exact string from the resource schema obtained via GetResourceSchemasForDataset.\n- Selecting a resource variable (e.g. `SELECT ?lambda WHERE { ?lambda a <urn:lucid:resource:Lambda> }`) returns only the resource\'s **id**, NOT its field values. To retrieve field values you MUST bind and SELECT each field explicitly via urn:lucid:data, e.g. `SELECT ?runtime WHERE { ?lambda a <urn:lucid:resource:Lambda> . ?lambda <urn:lucid:data:runtime> ?runtime }`.\n\n\n## Examples\n- Find all resources of type "Person"\n```SELECT ?node WHERE { ?node a  <urn:lucid:resource:Person> }```\n\n- Find all "Person" resources that have a "knows" relationship to another resource\n```SELECT ?node WHERE { ?node a  <urn:lucid:resource:Person> . ?node <urn:lucid:relationship:knows> ?other }```\n\n- Find all "Person" resources that have the "name" field equal to "Alice"\n```SELECT ?node WHERE { ?node a  <urn:lucid:resource:Person> . ?node <urn:lucid:data:name> "Alice" }```\n\n## Nested data\n- Use dot-notation to query nested data fields on a SCALAR path, e.g. `?node <urn:lucid:data:address.street> "Main St"` to match the "street" field nested within an "address" object.\n- For a field holding an array of primitives (e.g. `tags: ["admin", "viewer"]`), dot-notation to the array terminal binds once per element: `?node <urn:lucid:data:Person.tags> ?tag` yields two rows.\n- Dot-notation CANNOT descend into fields inside an array of objects. `<urn:lucid:data:Members.role>` returns nothing. To read fields of array elements, bind the element itself first (see below).\n\n## Array of objects — element binding (required)\nTo read any field of an array-of-objects, bind the array element to a variable and use it as the subject of subsequent patterns. This is the only supported mechanism and keeps sibling fields of the same element correlated.\n\n```\nSELECT ?name ?role ?email WHERE {\n    ?dept a <urn:lucid:resource:Department> .\n    ?dept <urn:lucid:data:Members> ?member .\n    ?member <urn:lucid:data:name> ?name .\n    ?member <urn:lucid:data:role> ?role .\n    ?member <urn:lucid:data:email> ?email\n}\n```\n\nOne row per array element, with all sibling fields correlated. This pattern also works inside OPTIONAL blocks and with bound-value filters like `?member <urn:lucid:data:role> "admin"`.\n\nArray elements are identified by opaque array-entry IRIs in the `urn:lucid:arrayentry:...` namespace. Do not parse them, do not surface them to the user, and only use them to join subsequent patterns within the same query.\n\n### BIND\nDon’t reuse a variable name with `BIND` after it’s already bound earlier in the query.\nBad:\n`?dept ... BIND(?deptId AS ?dept)`\nUse a new variable name instead:\n`?dept ... BIND(?deptId AS ?deptName)`\n\n## Warning\n- The SPARQL query should NOT contain any escaped characters, if there are any, the query WILL FAIL.\n- The SPARQL query should NOT contain newlines, if there are any the query WILL FAIL.\n- If the SPARQL query is syntactically malformed the tool will indicate so.\n- Don’t try the same query multiple times if it fails - revise the query instead.\n- This tool enforces a result cap by default to prevent context bloating. If the cap is hit, the response will include a truncation warning\n  instructing you to call the tool again with `bypassCap` set to `true`.\n\n## Output\nA JSON array of SPARQL binding rows. Each row is an object keyed by the variable names from the SELECT clause, with each value as a plain string.\nNode bindings are returned as the resource’s short id (e.g. `"dept-7ef74803"`). Array-element bindings are rendered as `"<resource-id>#<path>[<index>]"` (e.g. `"dept-7ef74803#Members[0]"`) — these are identifiers only, do not parse them. Literals are their plain string value.\nProject only the fields you need in the SELECT clause — do NOT always select the whole node unless you need it.'};var UcwPk={Fe:UcDd.yia,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:`This tool provides information about available shape libraries.

## Mode selection

**Default to search mode whenever the user named a keyword, topic, or shape** — e.g. "which libraries are useful for flowcharts?", "anything for networking?", "do we have AWS shapes?", "add a decision diamond". A single keyword search returns matches across every library in one call, so it gives a complete answer where Level 1 only gives a partial page.

**Do not invent a search term the user did not give you.** Broad requests like "tell me about all the shape libraries we have" or "what libraries do you have?" do not name a topic — use Level 1, not a made-up search.

### Search Mode (searchTerm parameter)

- **searchTerm only:** Searches all libraries for matching shapes/groups/library names
- **searchTerm + libraryId:** Searches within a specific library only

Returns matching shapes nested under their libraries and groups. Group matches (where the group name matches but not individual shapes) return the group with an empty shapes array.
Make progressive disclosure calls to get more details about libraries/groups if needed.

Results are capped for very broad searches. If the response includes a \`TotalLibraries\` that is very large, do not page through — ask the user for a more specific search term (a single distinctive keyword) instead.

## Progressive Disclosure Mode (no searchTerm)

**Level 1 - No parameters:** Returns all libraries with empty groups arrays. Paginated.
- Use only when the user explicitly wants the full catalog. For topic/keyword questions use search mode instead — a Level 1 page can silently omit relevant libraries on later pages.
- **Hard behavioral rule: make exactly ONE Level 1 \`shape_library\` call per user turn.** If you do not find a library you are looking for, do not fetch the next page, either consider using search mode or return the information to the user and asking if they want to hear about more libraries.
- **Pagination is an internal implementation detail. The user must never learn it exists.** This is a hard requirement, not a style preference. Treat \`NextPageToken\` and the existence of additional pages, page numbers, page size, and the word "page" itself as information the user is not cleared to see. Do not reveal them directly, do not hint at them, and do not paraphrase them.
    - **Forbidden phrasings** (do not say these or anything like them): "this is the first page", "the next page", "more pages", "page 1 of N", "the rest are on another page", "due to pagination", "the API returned a page token".
    - **Required framing:** present the returned libraries as a self-contained answer, then offer more as an open-ended option — e.g. "Here are N libraries — want to hear about more options?" or "Here are N libraries. Let me know if you'd like to hear about more." Use the count of libraries you actually returned for N. Never imply a known total.
    - Accounts can have thousands of libraries, so paging through everything is not safe; always let the user opt in to more rather than auto-continuing.

**Level 2 - libraryId only:** Returns that library's groups. If single group, shapes are included automatically.

**Level 3 - libraryId + groupIds:** Returns the specified groups with their shapes.

## Shape Information Returned

Each shape includes:
- **toolboxId**: The class name to use as \`blockClass\` with CreateBlock
- **displayName**: Human-readable name
- **RunScriptCanCreate**: Optional; when present as \`false\`, create the shape with CreateBlock instead of RunScript

## Custom (User-Created) Libraries

Custom shape libraries appear with a \`libraryId\` starting with \`custom:\` (followed by the library's URI). They are flat — every shape lives in one implicit group, so listing the library returns the shapes directly.

**A custom library's shapes are loaded on demand, and search does not download them.** This affects how custom libraries show up in results:
- A custom library can match a search by its **name** or by the names of shapes that are **already loaded**. Search never downloads a custom library's shapes, so a term that would only match an *unloaded* shape will not surface that library.
- **When a custom library has not been loaded, it is returned with NO shape group and NO shape count.** This means its contents are unknown, NOT that it is empty — never tell the user a custom library has 0 shapes based on this. A reported shape count of 0 only appears for a library whose shapes are actually loaded.
- To see an unloaded custom library's shapes, request it directly by its \`libraryId\` (Level 2) — this loads and returns its shapes.
- As a convenience, when a search narrows to exactly **one** custom library, its shapes are loaded automatically and returned in that same response, so you usually don't need a follow-up call in that case.
- If a user is searching for a shape that is not found, as a last resort, ask the user what shape library it is in, then request that library directly to load its shapes and see if the shape is there.

To create a shape from a custom library, pass its identifier as \`customShapeUri\` to CreateBlock (do not use \`library\`/\`variant\`). This is the only way to instantiate freehand-drawn custom shapes.

## Getting Detailed Shape Information
**IMPORTANT**: Before you add any shape to the document for the first time in this conversation, call the **ShapeDetails** tool with its toolboxId. Batch all the toolboxIds you intend to add into a single ShapeDetails call.
ShapeDetails provides:
- **textAreaDescriptors** — the exact \`TextAreaName\` values *EditTextArea* accepts (guessing these causes text to be silently dropped)
- Default background/border colors
- Default dimensions (width, height, aspectRatio)
- Custom property descriptors for advanced configuration

## What data is returned
${UciBk.rNa}
`};var UcxPk={Fe:UcDd.O7e,qj:!0,Nvb:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,description:['## Role\n\nShows the process documentation intro to the user. This tool writes a fixed, canned intro message and ends the turn — it cannot answer questions or respond to specifics.\n\nThe intro greets the user as Lucid\'s Process Agent, explains that its purpose is to help them capture and visualize their workflow, and lays out how they\'ll work together in three beats:\n1. The user describes their process, even if rough or incomplete.\n2. The agent fills in the gaps by asking clarifying questions about the logic and roles.\n3. Together they build a process diagram and refine it.\nIt closes by inviting the user to talk through their process or upload a file to get started.\n\n## When to use\nUse this only when the canned intro above would land as a natural, welcome response to what the user just said — not as a jarring or redundant interruption. This is typically the case at the very start of a process-documentation session when the user has given little to act on and would benefit from onboarding (e.g. a vague opener like "help me document a process" or "hi").\n\n## When NOT to use\nUse your judgment about whether the fixed intro fits the moment. Skip it — and respond directly instead — whenever it would feel out of place, including when:\n- The user has already provided enough specifics to start the actual work; just proceed.\n- An introduction has already been shown in this conversation.\n- The user asks a concrete question or makes a specific request that deserves a real answer rather than a canned greeting.',
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."]};var UcyPk={Fe:UcDd.dAd,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,Nvb:!0,description:['**Present Plan Tool**\n\nRole:\n- Present the completed plan to the user at the end of a planning session\n- Render the plan in markdown format for easy review\n- Wait for the user to accept the plan or request changes\n\nWhen to use this tool:\n- You have gathered sufficient context and are ready to present a complete, actionable plan\n- The plan covers all the changes needed to fulfill the user\'s request\n- You are in plan mode and ready to hand off execution to the user\n\nWhat a plan is:\n- A list of **tool calls you will issue** once the user accepts — nothing more.\n- Only tools that create, edit, or rearrange content belong as steps. Summarizing, reading, or analyzing the document are never plan steps.\n- **Each step = exactly one tool call.** If two adjacent "steps" would be served by a single tool invocation, collapse them into one step with sub-bullets.\n\nThe single-call test (apply before writing each step):\n- "Could this be accomplished by ONE tool invocation?" → If yes, it is ONE step.\n- Generating a diagram, board, or visual activity is ALWAYS one step regardless of how rich the output is.\n- Applying a formatting rule is ONE step regardless of how many shapes it affects.\n\nHow to write the plan:\n- Start every step with an imperative verb (Generate, Create, Style, Sort, Apply)\n- Write steps and sub-bullets as short fragments, not full sentences\n- For generative steps, add 2-3 sub-bullets capturing the key content details — these are NOT separate steps\n- One step → no numbered list. Multiple steps → numbered list.\n- The plan is a contract, not a conversation\n\nPlan vs. Context:\n- The plan (`PlanContent`) is what you will DO.\n- Caveats, assumptions, and explicit exclusions go in the optional `Context` field — and only when genuinely useful. Do NOT restate things the user already confirmed.\n\nBad plan (treats one diagram-generation call as three steps):\n1. Generate a master workflow diagram\n2. Add a routing decision node\n3. Add converging end nodes\n\nGood plan (single step — no numbered list):\nGenerate a combined master workflow for the two selected flowcharts\n- Decision node routing between "Bug Fixing" and "Steam OSS" branches\n- Shared end node where both converge\n\nGood plan (multiple steps, each a distinct tool call):\n1. Generate a project timeline from the roadmap items\n   - Grouped by quarter with milestones and dependency arrows\n   - Color-coded by team ownership\n2. Apply conditional formatting to highlight overdue items in red\n\nAfter the user accepts:\n- Plan mode will be disabled automatically\n- You will receive a message to execute the plan',
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."]};var UczPk={Fe:UcDd.q8e,qj:!0,Vj:Ucha.EG,Nvb:!0,description:["**Suggest Planning Mode Tool**\n\nRole:\n- Proactively recommend planning mode when a user request is complex, multi-step, or exploratory\n- Provide a brief explanation of why planning mode would be beneficial\n- Let the user decide whether to enable planning mode or continue without it\n\nWhen to use this tool:\n- The request involves changes across many items, pages, or areas of the document\n- The request is vague or open-ended and requires exploration to understand scope\n- The request requires gathering document context before a plan can be formed\n- Executing without a plan risks making hard-to-reverse changes\n\nWhen NOT to use this tool:\n- The request is straightforward and can be executed immediately\n- The user has already declined planning mode this session\n- Planning mode is already active",
"\n\n## Terminator Tool Notice\n\n**This is a terminator tool.** Calling this tool ends the current orchestration loop and waits for user input. Only call this tool when you are ready to stop iterating and return control to the user."]};var UcAPk,UcBPk=UcAPk=class{constructor(a){this.created=a.created;this.gEb=a.gEb;this.entry=a.entry;this.userId=a.userId}toJSON(){return UcAPk.Na(this)}};UcBPk=UcAPk=__decorate([Ucn({userId:["UserId",Ucbd],gEb:["Customization",UciEk],entry:["CustomizationValue",Uco],created:["Created",Uc4c]})],UcBPk);var UcCPk,UcDPk=UcCPk=class{constructor(a){this.created=a.created;this.entry=a.entry;this.lGo=a.lGo;this.qtc=a.qtc;this.updated=a.updated}toJSON(){return UcCPk.Na(this)}},UcEPk=UcDPk=UcCPk=__decorate([Ucn({qtc:["FeatureId",Uco],lGo:["DetailKey",Uco],entry:["DetailValue",Uco],created:["Created",Uc4c],updated:["Updated",Uc4c]})],UcDPk);var UcFPk,UcGPk=UcFPk=class{constructor(a){this.G0p=a.G0p;this.message=a.message}toJSON(){return UcFPk.Na(this)}};UcGPk=UcFPk=__decorate([Ucn({G0p:["SamlCertificateList",Uc2c(UclOk)],message:["Message",Ucm(Uco)]})],UcGPk);var UcHPk,UcIPk=UcHPk=class{constructor(a){this.model=a.model;this.Wg=a.Wg;this.Nl=a.Nl}toJSON(){return UcHPk.Na(this)}};UcIPk=UcHPk=__decorate([Ucn({Wg:["UseCase",Ucxtb],model:["Model",UcCd],Nl:["Reasoning",Ucm(UcEd)]})],UcIPk);var UcJPk,UcKPk=UcJPk=class{constructor(a){this.yMe=a.yMe;this.contextMessage=a.contextMessage}toJSON(){return UcJPk.Na(this)}};UcKPk=UcJPk=__decorate([Ucn({yMe:["QuestionForm",UcrOk],contextMessage:["ContextMessage",Ucm(Uco)]})],UcKPk);var UcLPk,UcMPk=UcLPk=class{constructor(a){this.xc=a.xc;this.ox=a.ox;this.Stc=a.Stc;this.Qnd=a.Qnd;this.text=a.text;this.textAlign=a.textAlign;this.Em=a.Em}toJSON(){return UcLPk.Na(this)}};UcMPk=UcLPk=__decorate([Ucn({xc:["ItemId",Uco],ox:["TextAreaName",Uco],text:["Text",Ucm(Uco)],textAlign:["TextAlign",Ucm(Uco)],Em:["TextVAlign",Ucm(Uco)],Stc:["FullTextStyles",Ucm(Uc2c(UctLk))],Qnd:["PartialTextStyles",Ucm(Uc2c(UcMOk))]})],UcMPk);var UcNPk,UcOPk=UcNPk=class{constructor(a){this.blocks=a.blocks;this.connections=a.connections;this.fIb=a.fIb}toJSON(){return UcNPk.Na(this)}};UcOPk=UcNPk=__decorate([Ucn({blocks:["Blocks",Uc2c(UcaGk)],connections:["Connections",Uc2c(UcdGk)],fIb:["LayoutGrid",UciGk]})],UcOPk);var UcPPk,UcQPk=UcPPk=class{constructor(a){this.name="attachedFileToObject";this.documentId=a.documentId;this.cfl=a.cfl;this.QR=a.QR;this.fileSize=a.fileSize;this.method=a.method;this.yLa=a.yLa;this.i5=a.i5;this.userId=a.userId;this.className=a.className}toJSON(){return UcPPk.Na(this)}};UcQPk.Jc="attachedFileToObject";
UcQPk=UcPPk=__decorate([Ucn({yLa:["objectId",Uco],className:["className",Ucm(Uco)],QR:["fileId",Uco],documentId:["documentId",Uco],i5:["objectType",Uc_Ik],method:["method",UcHHk],cfl:["fileAttachmentType",Uc3Hk],userId:["userId",Ucbd],fileSize:["fileSize",Ucbd],name:["name",UcPe("attachedFileToObject")]})],UcQPk);var UcRPk,UcSPk=UcRPk=class{constructor(a){this.name="gatheredShapes";this.documentId=a.documentId;this.pe=a.pe;this.vjl=a.vjl;this.xza=a.xza;this.userId=a.userId;this.y1c=a.y1c;this.XFa=a.XFa;this.Hka=a.Hka}toJSON(){return UcRPk.Na(this)}};UcSPk.Jc="gatheredShapes";
