i18n.get("team-csv-export-trial-lucidsuite");function UcbSk(a,b){const c=b.map((d,e)=>[`### ${e+1}. ${d.title}`,`- Group: ${d.group}`,`- Check: ${d.check}`].join("\n")).join("\n\n");return[`# ${a} Convention Review`,"",`You have a checklist of ${b.length} conventional rules for ${a} diagrams. **Evaluate each rule against the user's actual board** — do NOT simply echo the rule list back to the user.`,'\n## How to evaluate each rule\n- If you do not already have enough context to apply a rule, call `FilterCanvas` (or `CanvasQuery`) to inspect the relevant items.\n- Assign exactly one of four verdicts. Use these verdict names verbatim in the output — no synonyms (do not say "Issues", "Problems", "Suggestions", "Warnings", "Compliant", etc.):\n  - **Recommended change** — the rule applies AND the board clearly deviates from it with no plausible justification visible from the diagram. These are concrete changes the user should make. Cite specific shapes/entities/relationships as evidence.\n  - **Recommended check** — the rule applies AND the board appears to deviate, but the deviation could be intentional given the user\'s context (denormalization for performance, a documented exception, a domain-specific pattern, etc.). Explain both what you observed and why it might be OK so the user can decide.\n  - **Strength** — the rule applies AND the board follows it. Briefly note what the board does well here. **Examples**: "Data Type Mismatches" when PK/FK pairs exist and their types match → Strength (not N/A). "Primary Keys" when entities exist and each has a clear PK → Strength.\n  - **N/A** — the rule does not apply because **the construct it checks for is entirely absent from the board**. The test is: could you even attempt this check on this board? If no, N/A; if yes (and nothing went wrong), Strength. **Examples**: a parallel-gateway rule on a diagram with no gateways → N/A. "Data Type Mismatches" on a diagram with no foreign keys at all → N/A. "Data Type Mismatches" on a diagram WITH foreign keys whose types happen to match → NOT N/A, this is Strength.',
`- **Internally evaluate ALL ${b.length} rules** and assign each one a verdict in your reasoning. Do not skip any during evaluation. The output bullet list is a curated subset of those evaluations — see the output-format section below for which verdicts get emitted and which are dropped.`,"\n## Required output format\nCall `MessageUser` with markdown structured EXACTLY as follows. Adhere to this format verbatim — the user has explicitly requested this layout and any deviation (level-2 headers, tables, numbered findings, paragraph-style findings, etc.) is a defect:\n\n- The entire user-facing output is a single flat markdown bullet list. No headers, no preamble, no summary.",
`- The bullet list is a **curated subset** of the ${b.length} internal evaluations — its length will often be less than ${b.length}, and that is correct. Do NOT pad the list to make every rule appear; dropped rules simply do not have a bullet.`,'- One bullet per emitted finding. Each bullet uses this exact shape:\n    `* **<Verdict>** - **<Rule title>**: <one or two plain sentences with concrete evidence from the board.>`\n  - `<Verdict>` is exactly one of `Recommended change`, `Recommended check`, `Strength`, `N/A` — verbatim, no synonyms, no pluralization.\n  - `<Rule title>` is the rule title from the checklist below, verbatim (e.g. `Naming Inconsistencies`, `Primary Keys`).\n  - The bullet marker is `*` (not `-`). The separator between the verdict and the rule title is a literal ` - ` (space, hyphen, space). The `:` after the second bolded segment is required.\n- Order bullets by verdict priority: all `Recommended change` first, then all `Recommended check`, then `Strength`, then `N/A`. Within a verdict group, preserve checklist order.\n- **Cap on Strength**: include at most 2 `Strength` bullets in total — pick the two most informative. Any Strength beyond the first 2 is **dropped from the output entirely**: no bullet of any kind. The total bullet count shrinks accordingly.\n  - **Do NOT reclassify dropped Strength rules as N/A.** N/A is reserved exclusively for rules whose construct is absent from the board. A dropped Strength must NOT appear under any other verdict (no N/A bullet, no "compliant" bullet, no acknowledgment). It is simply absent from the bullet list. Concrete example: if you internally evaluate 5 Strengths and 0 N/As, the output contains exactly 2 Strength bullets and 0 N/A bullets — not 2 Strength bullets + 3 N/A bullets.\n- N/A bullets: emit one bullet per N/A rule (no cap), BUT only for rules whose subject is **literally absent** from the board. N/A is NOT a way to confirm you considered a rule, and it is NOT where dropped Strengths go. Pre-emission self-check: for every N/A bullet, write its body as `"No <subject> are present/shown/modeled on this board"`. If you find yourself writing `"No <bad-thing> are present"` (e.g. "No FK loops", "No duplicated attributes", "No mismatches"), STOP — the subject (FKs, attributes, columns) IS present and the board passed the check. That is a Strength, not N/A. If the Strength got dropped by the 2-cap, emit no bullet at all.\n  - Concrete contrast: "No M:N relationships exist on this board" → valid N/A (the subject — M:N relationships — is absent). "No circular FK loops between entities are present" → NOT N/A (relationships between entities exist; the board was checked and passed); this is Strength (subject to the 2-cap).\n- Do not use sub-bullets, nested lists, paragraphs between bullets, tables, or numbered lists. The bullet body is plain prose after the `:`.\n- Example bullets:\n    `* **Recommended change** - **Naming Inconsistencies**: Some entities use singular (\\`customer\\`) while others use plural (\\`orders\\`). Pick one convention and apply it across all entities.`\n    `* **Recommended check** - **Redundant Columns**: The \\`email\\` attribute appears on both \\`User\\` and \\`Profile\\`. This may be intentional denormalization for read performance — confirm before changing.`\n    `* **Strength** - **Primary Keys**: Every entity has a clearly marked unique identifier.`\n    `* **N/A** - **M:N without Junctions**: No many-to-many relationships exist in this diagram.`\n- Do not invent rules beyond the checklist.\n- Start the message with the first bullet. No preamble, no closing summary.\n\n## Required SuggestedActions on your MessageUser\nThese actions are not optional. The `MessageUser` call that delivers the findings MUST include them when their condition is met.\n\n### 1. Address-recommendations action (REQUIRED whenever any finding is a Recommended change or a Recommended check)\n- If ANY rule received a `Recommended change` or `Recommended check` verdict, your `MessageUser` call MUST include a `SuggestedAction` whose intent is to regenerate / redraw / rebuild the diagram to address those findings.\n- The action\'s `Label` MUST be EXACTLY: `Address recommendations`. Do not paraphrase, rename, translate, capitalize differently, or substitute synonyms. The user has specifically requested this wording.\n- The action\'s `Prompt` MUST embed every Recommended change and Recommended check finding inline, with concrete evidence, so the next turn has the context it needs. Omit Strength and N/A findings — they are not actionable.\n- Good example:\n    - Label: "Address recommendations"',
`    - Prompt: "Regenerate this ${a} addressing the following: (1) <short finding title> — <evidence>. (2) <short finding title> — <evidence>."`,'- Bad example (DO NOT do this — the next turn will have no idea which conventions to fix):\n    - Prompt: "Regenerate this board"\n- **OMIT this action entirely if every finding is a Strength or N/A** (i.e., zero Recommended change AND zero Recommended check findings). In that case, only the re-review action below should be present. Do not emit a fix action with an empty prompt or with placeholder text.\n\n### 2. Re-review action (REQUIRED on every review)\n- Your `MessageUser` call MUST also include a second `SuggestedAction` that re-invokes a conventional review on this same diagram type so the user can verify any fixes they make.',
`- The action's \`Label\` should be approximately: "Review this ${a} again".`,`- The action's \`Prompt\` should be approximately: "Run a conventional ${a} review on this board again."`,"- Include this action even when every finding is a Strength or N/A — the user may still iterate.\n\n## Rules to Check\n",c].join("\n")}
